# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jurassic-park-novel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In December 1975, Kelvin Gosnell, a sub-editor at IPC Magazines, read an article in the *London Evening Standard* about a wave of forthcoming science fiction films, and suggested that the company might get on the bandwagon by launching a science fiction comic.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] IPC publisher John Sanders asked Pat Mills, a freelance writer and editor who had created *Battle Picture Weekly* and *Action*, to develop it.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Mills brought fellow freelancer John Wagner on board as script adviser and the pair began to develop characters.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The then-futuristic name *2000 AD* was chosen by John Sanders, as no-one involved expected the comic to last that long.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The original logo and overall look of the comic were designed by art assistant Doug Church.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] IPC owned the rights to *Dan Dare*, and Mills decided to revive the character to add immediate public recognition for the title.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Paul DeSavery, who owned *Dare*'s film rights, offered to buy the new comic and give Mills and Wagner more creative control and a greater financial stake.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Mills' experiences with *Battle* and *Action* in particular had taught him that readers responded to his anti-authoritarian attitudes.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] This would allow the new comic to be as violent as *Action* had been – a comic which had generated much controversy – but without attracting criticism, because the violence would be committed by an officer of the law.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] As Sanders put it, "The formula was simple: *violence on the side of justice* ...
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Meanwhile, Mills had developed a horror strip, inspired by the novels of Dennis Wheatley, about a hanging judge, called *Judge Dread* (after the reggae and ska artist of the same name).
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The idea was abandoned as unsuitable for the new comic, but the name, with a little modification, was adopted by Wagner for his ultimate lawman.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The task of visualising the newly named *Judge Dredd* was given to Carlos Ezquerra, a Spanish artist who had previously worked with Mills on *Battle*, on a strip called *Major Eazy*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Wagner gave Ezquerra an advertisement for the film *Death Race 2000*, showing the character Frankenstein clad in black leather, as a suggestion for what the character should look like.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Ezquerra elaborated on this greatly, adding body-armour, zips and chains, which Wagner originally thought over the top.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Wagner's initial script was rewritten by Mills and drawn up by Ezquerra, but when the art came back a rethink was necessary.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The hardware and cityscapes Ezquerra had drawn were far more futuristic than the near-future setting originally intended, and Mills decided to run with it and set the strip further into the future.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] By this stage, however, Wagner and Ezquerra had both quit.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Mills was reluctant to lose *Judge Dredd*, and farmed the strip out to a variety of freelance writers, hoping to develop it further.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Their scripts were given to a variety of artists as Mills tried to find a strip which would make a good introduction to the character, all of which meant that *Dredd* would not be ready for the first issue.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The story chosen was one written by freelancer Peter Harris, extensively rewritten by Mills and including an idea suggested by Kelvin Gosnell, and drawn by newcomer Mike McMahon.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The strip debuted in prog 2, dated 5 March 1977.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Mills had also created *Harlem Heroes*, about the future sport of aeroball, a futuristic, violent version of basketball with jet-packs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Similar future sport series had been a fixture of *Action*, and the similarly themed film *Rollerball* had been released the previous year.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Wanting to give the new comic a distinctive look, Mills wanted to use European artists, but the work turned in on *Harlem Heroes* by Trigo was disappointing.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Veteran British artists Ron Turner and Barrie Mitchell were tried out, but the newcomer Dave Gibbons won the editor over with his dynamic, American-influenced drawings and got the job.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Mills wrote the first five episodes before handing the strip to *Roy of the Rovers* writer Tom Tully.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] After 16 issues, Mills quit as editor and handed the reins to Kelvin Gosnell, whose idea the comic had been in the first place.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Wagner returned to write *Judge Dredd*, starting in prog 9.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] His "Robot Wars" storyline was drawn by a rotating team of artists, including McMahon, Ezquerra, Turner and Ian Gibson, and marked the point where *Dredd* became the most popular character in the comic, a position he has rarely relinquished.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Dredd's city, which now covered most of the east coast of North America, became known as Mega-City One.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Dredd had also been unmasked in issue 8 in a story drawn by Massimo Belardinelli, but the decision was made to make out that Dredd's face had been scarred and the panel had a "censored" banner slapped on it.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] After this, there were no further attempts to show Dredd's face again.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A new story format was introduced in prog 25 – *Tharg's Future Shocks*, one-off twist-in-the-tale stories devised by writer Steve Moore.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] *2000 AD* still uses this format as filler and to try out new talent.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Wagner introduced a new character, *Robo-Hunter*, in 1978.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The hero, Sam Slade, was a private detective-type character specialising in robot-related cases.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] José Ferrer was the original artist, but the editorial team were not happy with his work and quickly replaced him with Ian Gibson, who redrew parts of Ferrer's episodes before taking over himself.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Gibson's imaginative, cartoony art helped drive the series' style from hard-boiled detective to surreal comedy.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] As the series continued Sam was joined by an idiot kit-built robot assistant, Hoagy, and after a crack-down on smoking in IPC comics, a Cuban robot cigar, Stogie, designed to help him cut down on nicotine.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In 1977 *2000 AD* launched the annual 48-page Summer Special, including a full-length *M.A.C.H.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The yearly hardcover annual also started in 1977 (cover dated 1978) and would continue till 1990 (dated 1991).
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Pat Mills took over writing *Dredd* for a six-month "epic" called "The Cursed Earth", inspired by Roger Zelazny's *Damnation Alley*, which took the future lawman out of the city on a humanitarian trek across the radioactive wasteland between the Mega-Cities.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] McMahon drew the bulk of the stories, with occasional episodes drawn by Brian Bolland.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The story saw Dredd moved to the colour centre pages for the first time while *Dan Dare* was given the front page.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Steve MacManus took over from Gosnell as editor in 1978, starting with prog 86, dated 14 October.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In that issue *2000 AD* merged with *Starlord*, a second science fiction comic which had been launched by IPC earlier that year.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] As Gosnell was editor of *Starlord* and *2000 AD* at the same time, *2000 AD* sub-editor Nick Landau largely edited the latter comic himself during this time.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] *Starlord* was cancelled after only 22 issues and merged into *2000 AD* from prog 86.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Two *Starlord* strips strengthened *2000 AD*'s line-up: *Strontium Dog*, a mutant bounty hunter created by Wagner and Ezquerra, and *Ro-Busters*, a robot disaster squad created by Mills.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] *Ro-Busters* gave O'Neill the chance to spread his artistic wings and led to the popular spin-off *ABC Warriors*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] *Strontium Dog* and *ABC Warriors* continued to feature in *2000 AD* for the next 40 years.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] (A third *Starlord* series, *Timequake*, only lasted for four episodes and was not renewed.) *Dan Dare* was suspended while "The Cursed Earth" was finished in time for the merger.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Wagner returned to *Dredd* following the merger to write "The Day the Law Died", another six-month epic in which Mega-City One was taken over by the insane Chief Judge Cal, based on the Roman emperor Caligula.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Another cancelled title, *Tornado*, was merged with *2000 AD* a few months later from prog 127, dated 25th August, 1979.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] These stories, unlike *Starlord's*, did not continue for very long.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The last issue titled *2000 AD and Tornado* was prog 177, dated 13 September 1980.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A feature of the early years of *2000 AD* was the opportunities it gave to young British comic artists: by the time the title celebrated its 100th issue Brian Bolland, Dave Gibbons, Ian Gibson, Mike McMahon and Kevin O'Neil were all established as regulars.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In 1980 *Judge Dredd* gained a new enemy.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Writer John Wagner realised that Dredd's habit of shooting just about everybody he came up against meant that it was difficult to create a recurring villain.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The solution was Judge Death, an undead judge from another dimension where, since all crime was committed by the living, life itself was outlawed.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The law had been thoroughly enforced on his own world, and now he had come to Mega-City One to continue his work.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Judge Death first appeared in an atmospheric three-parter drawn by Brian Bolland which also introduced Judge Anderson and Psi Division, a squad of judges with psychic powers.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Dredd soon began another epic journey in "The Judge Child".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A dying Psi Division Judge had predicted disaster for Mega-City One unless it was ruled by a boy with a birthmark shaped like an eagle, so Dredd set off into the Cursed Earth, to Texas City, and into deep space in search of the boy, Owen Krysler, and his kidnappers, the Angel Gang.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] All of them were killed during the course of the story, however the Mean Machine was later resurrected by Krysler during "Destiny's Angels".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] "The Judge Child" was drawn by Bolland, Ron Smith and Mike McMahon in rotation, and the later episodes marked the beginning of Wagner's long-running writing partnership with Alan Grant.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The pair would go on to write *Strontium Dog*, *Robo-Hunter* and many other stories for *2000 AD*, as well as for *Roy of the Rovers*, *Battle* and the relaunched *Eagle* in the United Kingdom, and a number of comics in America.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Pat Mills introduced *Comic Rock*, which was meant to be a format for short stories inspired by popular music.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The first story, inspired by The Jam's *Going Underground*, was drawn by Kevin O'Neill and featured a complicated underground travel network on a planet called "Termight", in which a freedom fighter called Nemesis battles the despotic Torquemada, chief of the Tube Police.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] All that was seen of Nemesis was the outside of his vehicle, the Blitzspear.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The story was a reaction to an earlier tube chase sequence Mills and O'Neill had done in *Ro-Busters*, which management objected to.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The only other *Comic Rock* story was a follow-up called "Killer Watt", in which Nemesis and Torquemada fought on a teleport system.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] This led to a series, *Nemesis the Warlock*, in which it was revealed that Termight was Earth in the far future.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Torquemada was changed from the Chief of Traffic Police to a despotic demagogue leading a campaign of genocide against all aliens, and Nemesis was the leader of the alien resistance.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Mills and O'Neill were on a roll and produced a stream of bizarre and imaginative ideas, but ultimately O'Neill was unable to continue the level of work he was putting into it on *2000 AD* pay.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] He left to work for DC Comics in America, and was replaced on *Nemesis* by first Jesus Redondo and then Bryan Talbot.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A readers' poll revealed that future war was a popular topic, so Gerry Finley-Day was asked to come up with a new war story.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] He, editor Steve MacManus and artist Dave Gibbons devised *Rogue Trooper*, a "Genetic Infantryman" engineered to be immune to chemical warfare hunting down the traitor general who had betrayed his regiment, who debuted in 1981.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] He was supported by bio-chips of the personalities of three dead comrades, which, slotted into his equipment, could talk to him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Gibbons left the strip early on and was replaced by Colin Wilson, Brett Ewins and Cam Kennedy.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] *Rogue Trooper* replaced *Meltdown Man*, which had recently ended its run.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Another new strip in 1981, inspired by the brief CB radio craze, was *Ace Trucking Co.*, a comedy about pointy-headed alien space trucker Ace Garp and his crew by Wagner, Grant and Belardinelli.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In the *Judge Dredd* series, Mega-City One had grown too large and unwieldy: therefore authors Wagner and Grant they planned to cut it down to size.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] "Block Mania", in which wars broke out between rival city-blocks, turned out to be a plot orchestrated by the Russian city East-Meg One, and led directly to "The Apocalypse War", another six-month epic and a hard-hitting satire on the concept of mutually assured destruction.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] East-Meg One, protected by a warp-shield, softened up Mega-City One with nuclear warheads before invading.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Dredd spearheaded the resistance, leading a small team to East-Meg territory, hijacking their nuclear bunkers and blowing East-Meg One off the face of the earth.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] "The Apocalypse War" was drawn in its entirety by Carlos Ezquerra, making a return to the character he created.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A new writer, Alan Moore, had started contributing *Future Shocks* in 1980.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] He wrote more than fifty one-off strips over the next three years, while also contributing to various Marvel UK titles and the independent magazine *Warrior*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In 1982 he gained his first series, *Skizz*, a less sentimental take on the same basic plot used in *E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial*, set in Birmingham and influenced by Alan Bleasdale's *Boys from the Blackstuff*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Moore wrote another series, *D.R. and Quinch*, spun off from a one-off *Time Twister*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Drawn by Alan Davis, the strip featured a pair of alien juvenile delinquents with a penchant for mindless thermonuclear destruction.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] He went on to create *The Ballad of Halo Jones* with artist Ian Gibson.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Halo was an everywoman in the far future, born into mass unemployment on a floating housing estate, who escaped the earth and became involved in a terrible galactic war.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Three books were published, and more were planned, but Moore's demands for creator's rights and his increasing commitments to American publishers meant they never materialised.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A new character, *Sláine*, debuted in 1983, but had been in development since 1981.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Created by Pat Mills and his then wife Angela Kincaid, *Sláine* was a barbarian fantasy strip based on Celtic mythology.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Kincaid was a children's book illustrator who had never worked in comics before, and her opening episode was drawn and redrawn several times before the editors were satisfied.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Other stories were written for artists Massimo Belardinelli and Mike McMahon, but these could not see print until Kincaid's episode was ready.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In 1985, after appearing as a supporting character in *Judge Dredd*, *Judge Anderson* finally appeared in her own series, written by Wagner and Grant and initially drawn by Brett Ewins.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] New artist Glenn Fabry debuted on *Sláine*, but, due to his slowness, he was rotated with David Pugh.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In the *Judge Dredd* story "Letter from a Democrat", Wagner and Grant introduced a pro-democracy movement in Mega-City One, which is after all a police state.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] This would provide plotlines for years to come.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In 1986 the comic reached its 500th issue.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A new *Sláine* story, *Sláine the King*, began, entirely drawn by Fabry.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Peter Milligan, a writer who had been contributing *Future Shocks*, began two series, the bleak future war story *Bad Company* and a strange, psychedelic series called *The Dead*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In 1987 IPC's comics division was hived off and sold to publishing magnate Robert Maxwell as Fleetway.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] *2000 AD* was revamped, with a larger page size and full process colour on the covers and centre pages.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Kevin O'Neill returned for a short *Nemesis* series called "Torquemada the God".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Not long after came the debut of *Zenith*, *2000 AD'*s first serious superhero strip, by new writer Grant Morrison and artist Steve Yeowell.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The title character was a shallow pop singer with superhuman powers, caught up in the intrigues of a 1960s generation of superhumans and the machinations of some Lovecraftian elder gods.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Wagner and Grant began a new *Dredd* Epic, "Oz", featuring Chopper, a popular supporting character.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Chopper was a skysurfer who had been imprisoned for competing in an illegal surfing competition a few years previously.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A legal "Supersurf" race was being held in Oz, the future Australia, and Chopper escaped to compete.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Dredd also went to Oz, partly to deal with Chopper, but mostly to investigate the Judda, a clone army created by Mega-City One's former chief genetic engineer.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The Judda were defeated, and Chopper narrowly lost the race to Jug McKenzie.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Dredd was waiting at the finish line, but McKenzie distracted him and allowed Chopper to escape into the outback.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] This ending was apparently the cause of some dispute between Wagner and Grant, and was a contributing factor (it was *The Last American*, a mini series for Epic Comics which would mark the end) in ending their regular writing partnership.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Wagner kept *Dredd*, while Grant continued *Strontium Dog* and *Judge Anderson*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] However the pair would still come together for occasional collaborations.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The "Oz" storyline had some lasting implications.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Kraken, a Judda cloned from the same genetic material as Dredd, was captured by Justice Department, who had plans for him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Chopper also spun off into his own series, written by Wagner and drawn by Colin MacNeil.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The *ABC Warriors* finally had their own series again in 1987 as a spin-off from *Nemesis*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] This was written, as ever, by Pat Mills, and drawn by two artists in rotation, newcomer Simon Bisley and science fiction artist S.M.S.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In 1988 Grant and artist Simon Harrison began a new *Strontium Dog* story, "The Final Solution".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] It took nearly two years to complete, and ended with the death of Johnny Alpha, who sacrificed his life to save mutants from extermination.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Original artist Carlos Ezquerra did not agree with the decision to kill the character off, and refused to draw it.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The number of colour pages was increased, allowing for one complete strip per issue to be painted.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Initially the colour pages were reserved for *Judge Dredd*, but were later given over to a new *Sláine* story, "The Horned God", fully painted by Simon Bisley.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The series was collected as a series of three graphic novels, then as a single volume, and has remained in print ever since.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In 1989 the colour pages were increased again, allowing for three colour stories and two black and white in every issue.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] One of the colour series was *Rogue Trooper: the War Machine*, written by Dave Gibbons and painted by Will Simpson.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] One of the black and white stories, "The Dead Man", was a low-key beginning for a major event.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In the Cursed Earth, villagers come across a man, burnt from head to toe, with no memory of who he is or what happened to him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] As he tries to piece his memories back together, he is being hunted by the evil beings who left him in that state.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A creepy, atmospheric horror-western, it was drawn by John Ridgway and written by "Keef Ripley", a pseudonym for John Wagner.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] By the end of the series the Dead Man had discovered his identity: he was Judge Dredd.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] As "The Dead Man" ended, a new *Judge Dredd* story, "Tale of the Dead Man", explained how Dredd had ended up in that position.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Dredd was getting older and the democratic movement was causing him to doubt his role, so Justice Department had groomed Kraken, the former Judda cloned from his bloodline, to replace him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Kraken was now ready for his final assessment, and Dredd himself was chosen to assess him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Although Kraken performed faultlessly, Dredd thought he perceived a hint of his former allegiance to the Judda in him, and failed him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] He then resigned as a judge and took the 'Long Walk' into the Cursed Earth.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] There he met the Sisters of Death, and only barely survived the encounter.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] This could mean only one thing: Judge Death was back.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] This set up the latest six-month epic, "Necropolis".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] After Dredd had left, Justice Department had put Kraken through one final test, and given him Dredd's badge.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] But the Sisters of Death, spirit beings from Judge Death's dimension, were able to use Kraken's inner conflict to take control of him and use him to bring Judge Death and the other Dark Judges back from the limbo dimension Dredd had exiled them to.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The Sisters possessed all the city's judges and began to enforce Death's twisted law.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Out in the Cursed Earth, Dredd had recovered his memory and returned to defeat the Dark Judges.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] He then tried to lance the democratic boil by holding a referendum on whether the Judges should continue to govern the city.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The judges won, by a small margin on a desultory turnout, and Dredd was satisfied.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The *Judge Dredd Megazine*, a monthly title set in the world of Dredd, was launched in October 1990.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] With John Wagner focusing his attentions there, Garth Ennis became the regular writer of Dredd in the weekly.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] American writer Michael Fleisher, who had written *The Spectre* and *Jonah Hex* in the 1970s, was recruited to write the continuing adventures of the new *Rogue Trooper*, along with several other strips, none of which went down very well.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Another new writer who failed to set *2000 AD* on fire was Mark Millar, whose revival of *Robo-Hunter* was particularly unpopular.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Millar has since gone on to become a successful writer of American superhero comics such as *The Authority* and *The Ultimates*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A new *ABC Warriors* series, written by Mills and Tony Skinner and painted by Kev Walker, began in 1991, in which Deadlock took over the warriors with his "Khaos" philosophy.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The old IPC strip *Kelly's Eye* was revived, by the new creative team of Alan McKenzie, Brett Ewins, and Zac Sandler, in 1993, when the publishers realized they no longer had the rights to the character.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Robert Maxwell died in late 1991, and Fleetway was merged with London Editions, a Danish-owned company that owned rights to Disney characters, to become Fleetway Editions.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In 1992, *2000 AD* and the *Judge Dredd Megazine* ran their first crossover story, "Judgement Day", in which zombies overran Mega-City One.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Written by Garth Ennis and drawn by Carlos Ezquerra, Peter Doherty, Dean Ormston and Chris Halls, the story teamed Judge Dredd with Johnny Alpha through the medium of time travel.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] John Smith and artist Paul Marshall created *Firekind*, a slow-paced story about dragons and alien societies, which was accidentally published with its episodes in the wrong order.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] However, in the 12-parter *The Darkest Star*, it transpires that the one to *actually* kill him was the Gronk himself; changed into a form designed by a cadre of Lyran necromancers to bring him endless agony, Alpha asked his friend to end his torment.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The "Summer Offensive" was an eight-week experiment in 1993, when new editor Alan McKenzie gave free rein to writers Grant Morrison, Mark Millar and John Smith, to a mixed reception.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Morrison wrote a Dredd story, "Inferno", and a drug-influenced comedy adventure, *Really & Truly*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Smith contributed *Slaughterbowl*, in which convicted criminals on dinosaurs are pitted against each other in a deadly sport, with the survivor being paroled for a year and granted wealth – but being forced to enter the Slaughterbowl again the next year.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Millar wrote *Maniac 5*, an action-packed series about a remote controlled war-robot.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] During this run was a satire of British tabloid attitudes titled *Big Dave*, written by Morrison and Millar and drawn by Steve Parkhouse.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] John Tomlinson became editor in 1994, and a second crossover between *2000 AD* and the *Megazine*, "Wilderlands", began.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Written by Wagner and drawn by Ezquerra, Mick Austin and Trevor Hairsine, it followed on from "Mechanismo", a series of stories in the *Megazine* in which Justice Department, opposed by Dredd, tried to introduce robot judges.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] With Wagner writing, *Judge Dredd* was again the flagship strip.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Former *Megazine* editor David Bishop became editor of the weekly in 1996 but sales continued to decline.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Unsuccessful series were dropped, and a number of new series were tried out, some more successful than others.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Writer Dan Abnett introduced *Sinister Dexter* in 1996, a strip about two hitmen influenced by the film *Pulp Fiction*, which became a regular feature.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In 1997, writer Robbie Morrison and artist Simon Fraser, who had worked with Bishop on the *Megazine*, created *Nikolai Dante*, a swashbuckling series set in future Russia starring a thief and ladies' man who discovers he's the illegitimate scion of an aristocratic dynasty.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] There were also gimmicks, like the "sex issue", sold in a clear plastic wrapper, *The Spacegirls*, a series attempting to cash in on the popularity of the Spice Girls, *B.L.A.I.R.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] 1*, a parody of Tony Blair based on *M.A.C.H.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] 1*, and an adaptation of the Danny Boyle film *A Life Less Ordinary*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A new *Dredd* epic, "Doomsday", appeared in 1999 and again ran in both *2000 AD* and the *Megazine*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] 1999 also saw the return of another character, *Nemesis the Warlock*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] After a break of ten years, writer Pat Mills decided to bring the story to an end with "The Final Conflict".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The series was drawn by Henry Flint in a style that recalled Kevin O'Neill's early work on the series, as well as Simon Bisley's *ABC Warriors* work.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The decade ended with a special 100-page issue called "Prog 2000".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Behind a cover by Brian Bolland, *Nemesis* wrapped up for good in a final episode drawn by Kevin O'Neill.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] War broke out in *Nikolai Dante*, and writer Gordon Rennie and artist Mark Harrison introduced future war story *Glimmer Rats*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Another old favourite, *Strontium Dog*, was revived by Wagner and Ezquerra, telling new stories of Johnny Alpha set before his death, with the conceit that previous stories had been "folklore" and the new stories were "what really happened", allowing Wagner to revise continuity.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The publisher has been owned by Rebellion Developments since 2000, with editors Andy Diggle and (since 2002) Matt Smith at the helm.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Rebellion continues to develop stories (and computer games) based on classic characters such as *Rogue Trooper* and *Judge Dredd*, and has also introduced a roster of new series including *Shakara*, *The Red Seas* and *Caballistics, Inc.*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] It has also published a tie-in to the film *Shaun of the Dead* in a story written by Simon Pegg and Edgar Wright.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The comic continues to uncover new British talents, including Boo Cook, Dom Reardon and Al Ewing.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] It has also benefited from an improved dollar-pound exchange rate that has meant the comic can now afford to re-employ some of the talent thought lost to America.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A number of shorter self-contained stories, partly created by the new wave of talent, have run including *London Falling*, *Stone Island* and *Zombo*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Other developments include a revamping of the *Judge Dredd Megazine* which has included a section acting as a showcase for British small press comics.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Starting in program 1500 was the Judge Dredd story "The Connection", a "prelude" to a 23-part Judge Dredd epic "Origins" which filled in a lot of the details about Dredd's past.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In prog 1526, dated 28 February 2007, *2000 AD* celebrated their 30th anniversary.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The issue saw the start of two new storylines: *Nikolai Dante* (by Robbie Morrison and Simon Fraser) and *Savage* (by Pat Mills and Charlie Adlard), along with a one-off episode of *Flesh* (by Pat Mills and Ramon Sola).
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The run-up to this saw the first arcs of new series *Stickleback* and *Kingdom*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] On 19 March 2012 the Royal Mail launched a special stamp collection to celebrate Britain's rich comic book history, which included *2000 AD*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In 2015 a documentary about the history of the comic was made, called *Future Shock!
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] On 1 October 2016, signings were held at comic shops in the UK, Ireland, Australia and the US to mark the publication of the 2000th prog.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In the same week a 40th birthday convention was announced, which was held in Hammersmith, London in February 2017.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] At the convention itself, it was announced by the Kingsley brothers that Rebellion would be willing to speak to outside software developers on developing *2000 AD'*s intellectual property.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In the same year, former editor Steve MacManus published his memoirs, *The Mighty One: My Life Inside The Nerve Centre*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In 2017, founding editor Pat Mills published his memoirs, *Be Pure!
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] 2000 AD and Judge Dredd: The Secret History*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Later in that year, Hachette Partworks began publishing *2000 AD: The Ultimate Collection*, initially an 80-volume fortnightly series of hardback books featuring classic stories from the first 40 years of the comic.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Now the Collection has been extended to 180 volumes.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] This followed the success of *Judge Dredd: The Mega Collection*, which had started in 2015 and later been extended to 90 volumes.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In June 2018 (July in the United States) a special issue was published, the *2000 AD Sci-Fi Special 2018*, which contained stories written and illustrated entirely by women.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Starting in May 2019, *2000 AD* began publishing periodic "all ages" issues every quarter, marketed as *2000 AD Regened*, and targeted at younger readers.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In these sixteen issues, *Judge Dredd* was replaced by *Cadet Dredd* stories.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Although there is no overall shared universe containing all *2000 AD* stories, some stories spin-off or crossover into other stories.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] These include the numerous stories that occur in the Judge Dredd universe.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Many stories by Pat Mills, which are frequently interlinked, link into the Dredd universe as well, though have been partially retconned by the writer.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Many stories written by Ian Edginton feature shared themes and references.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A long-running theme is that the editor of *2000 AD* is Tharg the Mighty, a green extraterrestrial from Betelgeuse who terms his readers "Earthlets".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Tharg uses other unique alien expressions and even appears in his own comic strips.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Readers sometimes play along with this; for example, in prog 201 a pair of readers wrote to Tharg claiming that they preferred to be called "Terrans"; the resulting controversy ended in Tharg allowing readers to vote for the preferred term in prog 229.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In prog 240 Tharg announced that the result was a draw, and "Terran" became an accepted term for readers' letters in the Nerve Centre.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] In similar vein, Tharg used to draw distinction between male and female letter-writers with "Earthlet" and "Earthlette" until a letter was printed in Prog 314 complaining about the use, and Tharg agreed to use "Earthlet" (or "Terran") regardless of gender.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] From prog 531 the term "Earthlette" was reintroduced.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Another running theme is Tharg's use of robots to draw and write the strips, which bear a marked resemblance to the actual writers and artists.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A fictional reason for Tharg to use mechanical assistance was given when the robots "went on strike" (reflecting real-life industrial action that occasionally halted IPC's comics production during the 1970s and 1980s).
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Tharg wrote and drew a whole issue himself, but when he ran it through the quality-control "Thrill-meter", the device melted down on extreme overload.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The offending issue had to be taken away, by blindfolded security guards, to a lead-lined vault where there was no danger of anyone seeing it accidentally.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Kelvin Gosnell, #17–85 (1977–1978) Assistant editor Nick Landau largely edited the comic himself in 1978 while Gosnell was occupied with editing new sister title *Starlord*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Starting in December 2004, an additional editor's note, titled "Damage Control", began appearing in the legal fine print at the bottom of the first page of every issue.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] This editor's note is written not from the perspective of Tharg but from that of Matt Smith, the sitting editor since "Damage Control" started.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Many of these have since moved on to work for American publishers such as DC Comics (especially the Vertigo and Wildstorm imprints) and Marvel Comics.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The first *2000AD* video games for 8-bit computers were two games based on *Strontium Dog* published by Quicksilva in 1984 for the ZX Spectrum and Commodore 64.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Melbourne House released the first *Judge Dredd* game on the Commodore 64 in 1986 and ZX Spectrum the following year.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The second *Judge Dredd* game was published by Virgin Games in 1991 for the Amiga, Atari ST, Amstrad CPC, Commodore 64, and ZX Spectrum platforms.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Martech produced two titles, *Nemesis the Warlock* and *Sláine*, while Piranha Software only published one *2000AD* video game, *Rogue Trooper* (written by Design Design) it had games based on *Judge Death* and *Halo Jones* in development which were never released.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A *Judge Dredd* arcade game was created but never completed nor released.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] It can be found online, where it is available for free, but requires an arcade / coin-op emulator.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] It features Mean Machine and other Angel Gang members.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A *Judge Dredd Pinball* game was released for MS-DOS in 1998.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] The same year saw the release of a Judge Dredd videogame for the Sony PlayStation which was developed by Gremlin Interactive and published by Activision.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] With the purchase of *2000 AD* by Rebellion Developments, a computer game company, several more *2000 AD*-linked games have been released or are under development.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] Death* was released in 2003 and *Rogue Trooper* followed in 2006 for the Xbox, PlayStation 2 and Microsoft Windows.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] An updated version for the Wii entitled *Rogue Trooper: Quartz Zone Massacre* was released in December 2009.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p01] A licensed Judge Dredd choose your own adventure style game "Judge Dredd: Countdown Sector 106" was released in 2012 by Australian and UK-based Tin Man Games for iOS, subsequently for Google Play and Steam.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p02] Logan, frustrated at the lack of activity from the comic's publishers both in promoting the title and also in making best use of new talents, decided to create an independent title using *2000 AD* copyrighted characters and situations.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p02] This was titled *Class of '79*, named after the year of Dredd's graduation from the Academy of Law – 2079.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p02] The first couple of issues contained work from now-professional comics creators Rufus Dayglo, Boo Cook, Henry Flint and PJ Holden and won the best Self Published/Independent Comic Award at the 1999 National Comics Awards.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p02] Lewis created *Zarjaz* comic, with strips featuring characters from a variety of *2000 AD* stories.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p02] There were also interviews with Alan Grant, Frazer Irving and Alan Moore, as well as an extensive article on breaking into comics as a writer.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p02] Another long-running fanzine, dedicated to the world of Johnny Alpha, is *Dogbreath*, originally run by the pseudonymous Dr Bob it is now being produced by FutureQuake Publishing.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p02] In 2003, Arthur Wyatt created *FutureQuake*, a fanzine devoted to the Future Shocks format.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p02] Although *Class of '79* and *FutureQuake* now appear to be on hiatus, the other titles are in continuous publication, *Zarjaz* having started up again with a new issue 1.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/2000-ad-comics-p02] In addition, a number of small press comics have emerged from the *2000 AD* fanbase, including *Solar Wind*, *Omnivistascope* and *The End Is Nigh*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] The novel was adapted into the 1972 film *The Carey Treatment*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] It was re-released in 1993 under Crichton's own name.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] The novel tackles the issues of abortion and racism as they were in late 1960s America and includes several non-fiction appendixes.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] John Berry is a pathologist working in Boston when abortion is illegal in the United States.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Berry's colleague, obstetrician Arthur Lee, has been arrested for performing an abortion that led to the death of 17-year old Karen Randall, a member of a prominent Boston medical dynasty.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Berry helped Lee disguise medical samples to hide the fact that Lee's dilation and curettage patients were pregnant.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Berry pretends to be Lee's lawyer to visit him in jail.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Lee insists he did not perform the abortion.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Berry sets out to prove Lee's innocence.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] He is beset by a hostile police captain and J.D.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Randall, a prominent surgeon and Karen's father.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] He eventually discovers Karen was promiscuous and a heavy drug user.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Berry discovers that Peter Randall, Karen's uncle, had already performed three abortions for Karen.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] However, when she asked for a fourth, Peter refused.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Berry confirms that Karen was not pregnant.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] He deduces that she had a benign thyroid tumor which was presenting symptoms of pregnancy.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Following the trail of Karen's life, Berry comes across a nurse named Angela and a drug dealer named Roman.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] He asks Roman about Karen, but he denies ever meeting her.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] While he follows Roman, he is brutally attacked.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] He ends up in the emergency room with severe cuts to his face and internal bleeding.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] While he is there, Roman and Angela are admitted.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Knowing she is a morphine addict and a nurse, Berry pretends to inject her with Nalorphine, having replaced it with water.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Angela falls for the placebo and begs for morphine to counteract the withdrawal symptoms.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] She confesses to performing Karen's abortion with Roman in exchange for drug money.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Roman had tried to kill Angela because she could link him to Karen.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] When her uncle happened on the scene, he hit Roman with a chair and killed him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Berry convinces him to tell the police what happened.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Lee decides to move to California to start over after being revealed as an abortionist, despite being exonerated for Karen's death.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Crichton had published several novels under the pseudonym John Lange but felt since this one was more serious than the Lange books it needed to come out under a different name.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] He planned to write further Jeffrey Hudson books about medical fiction, but this did not come about.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] The pen name Jeffrey Hudson came from the name of a dwarf in the time of King Charles I of England, who was served to the monarch in a pie and later captured by Barbary Pirates.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] The novel was republished in hardcover under Crichton's name in 1993.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-case-of-need] Crichton was furious at this, called the action "despicable", and said it misled the public into thinking it was a new novel.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-murder-in-hollywood] A Hollywood movie, *Bloodrock*, is being filmed in Tucson, Arizona.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-murder-in-hollywood] A screenwriter is found dead in his motel room during the shoot.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-murder-in-hollywood] The brilliant insurance investigator, Harlow Perkins, is called in to find out what happened.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-murder-in-hollywood] He works with the film's unit publicist, Harvey Jason.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/a-murder-in-hollywood] In *Booklist*, David Pitt wrote that the book made for an enjoyable read and described it as a "darned good book".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] While Costa Rica does not have an official air force, it has an air wing attached to the Public Force of Costa Rica.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] Currently this unit, officially called **Air Vigilance Service** (Spanish: *Servicio de Vigilancia Aérea* [SVA]), also called the Air Service (*Servicio Aéreo*), does not operate any armed military aircraft.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] Its main air bases located in three different points, San José (Base 2) being the main operations center.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] Some of the most common functions of the SVA are transporting civilians in critical medical emergencies to the hospitals in the capital as well as helping in the war on drugs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] Plenty of drug trafficking operations are carried in joint agreement with the U.S., mainly occurring in the coastal areas and at sea.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] According to a new bill yet to be passed by the Legislative Assembly, the new designation for this police air wing would be Policia de Vigilancia Aérea (Air Vigilance Police).
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] Costa Rica is one of the oldest democracies in the region and formally abolished its army on December 1, 1949, just after the end of a revolution that reformed the country's political structures.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] The internal security of the country was administered by the Civil Guard that, over the years, has transformed into what it is now, the Public Forces of Costa Rica, under the command of the Ministry of Public Security.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] It is composed of several departments: Public Force, Anti-Drug Police, National Coast Guard Service, National Police School, Reserve of the Public Force and the Air Surveillance Service, itself a successor of the Costa Rican Air Force.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] In 1958, the air wing was created with a Cessna 180 for the transportation of government officials and in 1962 it acquired three Cessna 185s.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] Later in 1970, it acquired a helicopter for use by the President.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] In 1994, it was renamed the Air Vigilance Service (Spanish: Servicio de Vigilancia Aérea, SVA), with 15 aircraft.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] As a result of the many operations against drug trafficking, a number of aircraft have been added to the asset list by means of confiscation.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] The U.S. has also donated aircraft, equipment and logistic support.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/air-vigilance-service] The prefix for most aircraft is MSP followed by a serial number.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] TransPacific Airlines Flight 545 experiences severe pitch oscillations over the Pacific Ocean, leading to dozens of injured passengers and several deaths.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] The plane, a Norton Aircraft N-22 widebody, has an excellent safety record, and the captain is highly skilled, making the possibility of human error seemingly unlikely.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Casey Singleton, a vice-president in quality assurance at Norton, is assigned by COO John Marder to join the company's Incident Review Team (IRT) to investigate.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] The IRT has one week to identify the issue in order to prevent a major sale with China from falling apart over safety concerns.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Due to issues with the flight recorders, the IRT is forced to manually check each system of the aircraft.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] At first, all signs point to the plane's slats accidentally deploying mid-flight.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Though other N-22s had exhibited similar slat errors in the past, Norton assumed the problem had been fixed.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Their search uncovers a counterfeit part in the wing, but this would not have been enough to cause the accident on its own.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Casey grows suspicious of Bob Richman, an arrogant Norton employee who has been assigned to assist her.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Meanwhile, the factory union is concerned the China sale will offset the wing to China, threatening employees' jobs, and seeks to sabotage the deal.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] An unrelated N-22 engine failure, and the release of passenger camera footage from Flight 545, draws heavy media attention.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Jennifer Malone, a producer for the television magazine *Newsline*, is interested in reporting on the N-22's flaws and pursues the story; Marder asks Casey to conduct an interview.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Later, Casey realizes the accident aircraft was equipped with a quick access recorder (QAR); the team did not know the plane was equipped with one because QARs are optional.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Casey locates the QAR and pieces together the events that caused the accident.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] First, a counterfeit part caused a sensor in the plane's wing to malfunction, which produced an error message in the cockpit.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] This error message could be cleared by deploying and retracting the plane's slats.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Although deploying the slats would change the shape of the wing, the autopilot could adjust without incident.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] However, the captain's son, a pilot who was not certified to fly the N-22, was at the controls at the time of the accident; he manually overcorrected, overriding the autopilot and sending the plane into a series of oscillations.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Casey realizes she cannot publicize this information.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Publicly pinning the blame on a TransPacific employee would sour relations with the airline, ruining future sales just as surely as any N-22 safety issues would.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] During her interview, she also discovers Richman has set her up to fail as part of a larger conspiracy.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Richman and Marder had secretly prepared a larger sale to a South Korean airline, which included offsetting the wing.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] They hoped to use the accident to sink the China deal and oust CEO Harold Edgarton, confident that the accident would not jeopardize the Korean deal.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Casey thwarts the plan by allowing Malone onto a test flight for the N-22 from the accident, where the event is replicated, showing that a slat deployment alone would not cause the accident.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Once Malone is shown the evidence, she cannot air her segment as planned without opening herself up to a defamation lawsuit.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] She is also unable to report the true story, since her boss thinks it is not exciting enough to hold people's attention.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] With the N-22's reputation cleared, the China deal proceeds, with the tail rather than the wing as an offset.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Afterwards, Edgarton promotes Casey to head the company's Media Relations Division.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Richman is arrested in Singapore for narcotics possession, while Marder leaves the company, supposedly on good terms.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Malone leaves *Newsline* after a "contract dispute", and joins the staff of *Hard Copy*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Air safety procedures are a central theme in the novel.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Another central theme, which compounds the issue mentioned above, is investigative journalism, and the consequences when sensational media agencies distort the truth to produce a better-selling story.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] The TV journalism subplot was singled out for praise in some reviews; *Entertainment Weekly* lauded it as "brutal and fresh and very funny" satire.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] In *Airframe*, as in most of his novels, Crichton uses the literary device of false documents, presenting numerous technical documents to create a sense of authenticity.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] He also takes great pains to be as accurate as possible in the novel's technical details.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] When the characters discuss how unfavorable media coverage can be the undoing of a perfectly good aircraft, his account of the American Airlines Flight 191 crash and its causes are consistent with the known facts at the time the novel was written.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Reviews tempered their praise with criticism of Crichton's writing style.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] Though the central accident in *Airframe* primarily resembles China Eastern Airlines Flight 583 and Aeroflot Flight 593, Mark Lawson of *The Guardian* accused Crichton and his publishers of trying to capitalize on a different airplane disaster.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/airframe-novel] An adaptation of *Airframe*, alongside an adaptation of *Eaters of the Dead*, was in development in the 1990s with Crichton and John McTiernan producing both, and writer William Wisher Jr. penning the screenplay adaptation.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] **Alan Grant** is a fictional character in the *Jurassic Park* franchise.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He is a paleontologist and is introduced in Michael Crichton's 1990 novel *Jurassic Park*, which began the franchise.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Crichton based Grant on the paleontologist Jack Horner who was by happenstance technical advisor for the movies.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Director Steven Spielberg helmed the 1993 film adaptation, and several actors were considered for the role of Grant.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] It ultimately went to Sam Neill, becoming one of his most popular roles.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Spielberg gave the character a dislike of children, and put him in a relationship with Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Ellie Sattler, a paleobotanist who is Grant's student in the novel.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Sattler, portrayed by Laura Dern, wants to start a family with Grant, who is resistant to the idea.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill reprised the character in 2001's *Jurassic Park III*, which also saw a cameo by Dern.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] In the film, Sattler has married someone else and started a family, although she and Grant remain friends.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Director Joe Johnston chose to break-up Grant and Sattler, believing that Dern looked too young to be in such a relationship; Neill is 20 years older than her.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill was dissatisfied with his performance in the first film, which factored into his return for *Jurassic Park III*, marking the first time he reprised one of his roles.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill and Dern would return again for major roles in *Jurassic World Dominion*, released in 2022.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] In the film, Sattler has divorced her husband; she and Grant eventually rekindle their romantic relationship.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Colin Trevorrow, the film's director and co-writer, was in agreement with Neill and Dern on reuniting their characters romantically.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill and Dern also reprised their roles for the video games *Jurassic World Evolution* and *Jurassic World Evolution 2*, lending their voices to downloadable content packs released in 2019 and 2022 respectively.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Alan Grant is a paleontologist who is dedicated to his research, which includes a focus on velociraptors.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He believes that dinosaurs are closely related to birds, and also theorizes that the vision of a *Tyrannosaurus* is based on movement.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant has written several books on dinosaurs, as referenced in the first novel.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He has also written at least two in the film series.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] In *Jurassic Park III*, Eric Kirby opines that he liked Grant's first book better, as Grant liked dinosaurs when he wrote it, compared to the second written after his time at Jurassic Park.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant has a dislike of computers, and is portrayed in the film series as easily irritated.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] In the first novel, Grant is described as "a barrel-chested, bearded man of forty".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He had a wife who died years prior to the events of the novel.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He has a strong affinity for children, especially those interested in dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He is one of the world's most renowned paleontologists, partly specializing in hadrosaur and other duck-billed dinosaurs such as *Maiasaura*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Ellie Sattler is a graduate student and paleobotanist who is studying under Grant.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Before the events of the novel, Grant was approached by Donald Gennaro, chief counsel for InGen, to provide information on the requirements for the care of infant dinosaurs, claiming it to be for a museum exhibit.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Later, John Hammond's investors demand that he bring experts to his island, Isla Nublar, to certify the safety of a new theme park he is building there called Jurassic Park.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant and Sattler agree to Hammond's invitation to tour the park, finding it difficult to turn down the request from a major financial donor.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Ian Malcolm, and are awestruck to learn that Hammond has cloned living dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] When the creatures escape, Grant becomes stranded in the park with Hammond's grandchildren, Lex and Tim.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Throughout a large portion of the book, Grant and the children explore the park trying to find their way back to the rest of the group.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant does not appear in Michael Crichton's sequel novel, *The Lost World*, but he is mentioned several times, including an instance stating that he is lecturing in Paris.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] The film adaptation of *Jurassic Park* generally uses the same story and characters as the novel, though with some differences.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] For example, Grant is given an introverted personality and a dislike of children.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] The film also depicts him in a relationship with Ellie Sattler, as opposed to her being his graduate student.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] She wants to have a child, but Grant is resistant to the idea of starting a family.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] However, over the course of the film, he warms up to Hammond's grandchildren and protects them.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Malcolm flirts with Sattler on several occasions, to the annoyance of Grant.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] In *Jurassic Park III*, Grant and Sattler had ended their romantic relationship on good terms sometime after the first film, but they still remain close friends.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Sattler has a minor role, and is now married to Mark, an employee of the U.S.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] In the years following the incident on Isla Nublar, Grant has continued his research on fossils, but he struggles to secure financing now that living dinosaurs are known to exist on InGen's Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He dismisses the notion that his research is moot, saying that InGen's creatures are just "genetically engineered theme park monsters" and not real dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant has proposed new theories regarding raptor intelligence, which he discusses with Sattler while visiting her.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He believes that raptors were incredibly smart and possessed advanced communication abilities.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Despite this, since the Jurassic Park disaster, Grant has developed an intense fear against raptors.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Later in the film, Grant reluctantly agrees to provide an aerial tour of Isla Sorna for the Kirbys, an allegedly wealthy couple, who agree to fund his dig site in exchange.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant and the Kirbys fly to Isla Sorna along with mercenaries and Grant's graduate student, Billy Brennan.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant is amazed, when they reach the island, having forgotten what it is like to see living dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] But the plane crashes and the group become stranded on the island.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant learns that the Kirbys are a divorced middle-class couple searching for their 12-year-old son, Eric, who went missing eight weeks earlier while parasailing near the island.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] The Kirbys brought Grant for his expertise, hoping it would come in handy during their search.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Eric is later found, and he and Grant bond while navigating Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant also realizes that his theories about raptors are correct.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He and the other survivors eventually find a satellite phone, which he uses to contact Sattler for help.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant, who is now an older man with no family, has continued his work in paleontology.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] His digs have not been receiving sufficient fundings, due to de-extinct dinosaurs spreading all over the world.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] This forces Alan to turn them as tourist attractions to stay afloat and to promote the importance of paleontology is to learn what life was like before humans became dominant species.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Ellie and Mark have separated, and their children are in college.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Now working as a soil scientist, she launches an investigation when giant locusts emerge and begin rapidly consuming crops, threatening the world's food supply.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Ellie learns that the insects are bypassing crops which use Biosyn's seeds, leading her to suspect that the company has engineered the insects to boost its own profits.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant and Ellie have not seen each other for some time.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] She visits him at his dig site in Utah and convinces him to accompany her to Biosyn's headquarters in Italy, to look for incriminating evidence.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] They receive help from Malcolm, who now works for the company as an in-house philosopher.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] While at Biosyn, Grant and Ellie meet Maisie Lockwood and her adoptive parents, Owen Grady and Claire Dearing.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant and Ellie rekindle their romantic relationship, and prepare to testify about Biosyn in Washington, D.C.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] In *Jurassic World Rebirth*, it is mentioned that Grant mentored Henry Loomis (Jonathan Bailey) after the latter earned his PhD in paleontology as a postdoctoral researcher.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Like Grant, Loomis is also compassionate with people.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant is a playable character in several early *Jurassic Park* video games based on the first film, as well as the 1994 games *Jurassic Park: Rampage Edition* and *Jurassic Park 2: The Chaos Continues*, and the 2001 game *Jurassic Park III: Island Attack*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He also appears in the 2003 game *Jurassic Park: Operation Genesis*, as the paleontologist responsible for locating material to clone dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant also makes an appearance in the 2019 miniseries *Lego Jurassic World: Legend of Isla Nublar*, and in a 2020 episode of *Animaniacs*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Crichton based Grant on the paleontologist Jack Horner.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant's scientific achievements, including the first description of maiasaurs, are actually those of Horner and Robert R.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant has also been compared to paleontologist Philip J.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] For the 1993 film adaptation, Grant's introverted personality and dislike of children were implemented because director Steven Spielberg wanted to "provide a source of dramatic tension that did not exist in the novel".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Screenwriter David Koepp stated that while the book was able to pull off having a lead character without a personal issue, the medium of film required the audience to have an emotional investment, so Grant's dislike of children was invented.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Sam Neill was one of Spielberg's first choices to play the role, although he was busy filming *Family Pictures*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Richard Dreyfuss and Kurt Russell seemed like obvious choices to Spielberg – the former having worked with him on *Jaws* (1975) – although he considered them both too expensive.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Tim Robbins and Harrison Ford received offers to play Grant.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Ford had previously worked with Spielberg, portraying Indiana Jones in several films during the 1980s.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Ford received a copy of the *Jurassic Park* script, but according to Spielberg, he "just said . . . at this point in his life and career, this wasn't his cup of tea".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] The role was also offered to William Hurt, but he declined it before reading the script, with Spielberg again saying that "it didn't sound like the kind of movie he would be interested in making at this time in his life".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill was ultimately cast in the role a few weeks prior to filming, with the start of production being adjusted to fit his schedule.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill was hesitant about taking a lead role, and was surprised to have received the offer.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Horner coached Neill on his acting performance.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill, a resident of New Zealand, spent weeks trying to perfect an American accent.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] When filming began, Spielberg told him he could use his regular voice.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] However, after several days, Spielberg advised Neill to speak somewhere in between the two accents.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] This was done at the suggestion of Neill, who considered it a realistic response for someone who has devoted their research to dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Spielberg made Grant and Sattler a couple in order to add tension to the film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He also felt that Sattler did not get enough attention in the book.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] She is played in the film by Laura Dern.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] There is a 20-year age difference between her and Neill, which goes unmentioned in the film and its sequels.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill said this was "a completely appropriate age difference for a leading man and lady" at the time.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Of his character's reluctance to starting a family, Neill said: "It's not that Grant dislikes children particularly, it's just that he is too caught up in his professional life to have time or energy for them.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] When Neill took the role as Grant, he signed on to appear in two potential sequels.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] *Jurassic Park III*, released in 2001, marked the first time that Neill had reprised one of his roles.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Reviews had been critical of the characters in the first film, and Neill believed that his performance could have been better, saying, "I was so over-awed by Spielberg; I think I didn't quite look after my guy [Grant] as well as I might have".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill reprised the role in order to get it "right this time", and to "fill in a few blanks", believing the character to be "a bit unresolved" after the first film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He said about his character: "I thought he'd be a little more gnarly than in the previous film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] The model in the back of my head was Lee Marvin in [1967's] 'Point Blank,' a guy who'd been through the mill before".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill was satisfied with his new performance, but found the role to be more physical than his previous films, as it included climbing, jumping, running, and swimming.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill was saddened by the break-up of Grant and Sattler, but said that his character was so "anti-child in the first film she needed someone else".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He liked how the script handled their break-up, with the two remaining close friends.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] In an early draft, Grant and Sattler were a couple in the process of splitting up.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] However, Johnston said: "I didn't want to see them as a couple anymore.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] For one thing, I don't think they look like a couple.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] It would be uncomfortable to still see them together.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] And Laura Dern doesn't look like she's aged for the past fifteen years!" Although Grant has a dislike of children, Neill noted that the character gets along well with the ones he encounters.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Of the two *Jurassic Park* films that Neill had appeared in, his favorite scene was in the latter, when Grant bonds with Eric Kirby and talks about his dinosaur books.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill was open to reprising his role for *Jurassic Park IV*, and was expected to return at one point.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] However, the project was delayed multiple times, eventually releasing in 2015 as *Jurassic World*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill and Dern do not appear in the film, which introduces new cast members.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Colin Trevorrow, the film's director and co-writer, did not want to feature Grant or other original characters without a compelling reason to involve them in the story.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Following its release, Neill did not anticipate that he and Dern would return to the film series, given its new direction.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He speculated in 2016 that Grant had either died, or had retired from paleontology to pursue accounting: "He's sick to death of dinosaurs and running. [...] How do you recover from all of that stuff?
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] I don't think therapists are trained to deal with post-dino stuff.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill and Dern eventually reprised their roles for *Return to Jurassic Park*, a downloadable content (DLC) pack released in 2019 for the game *Jurassic World Evolution*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] The two lent their voices, but had to record their lines separately due to scheduling conflicts.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] It was also announced in 2019 that Neill, Dern, and Malcolm actor Jeff Goldblum would return in *Jurassic World Dominion*, which released three years later.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] It marked the trio's first appearance together since the original *Jurassic Park* film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Trevorrow returned as director and co-writer, and the actors collaborated with him on their character portrayal.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] They were not interested in reprising their characters simply for a cameo, and Trevorrow shared their sentiment, placing them in major roles.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Trevorrow considered the actors to be the ultimate authority on their characters.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill said about Grant, "People don't change that much.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill kept his boots from the first film, and compared Grant to a pair of old boots: "They've seen better days, but they're really comfortable, and there's no way you'll get rid of those".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Trevorrow, Dern and Neill were in agreement on having Grant and Sattler reunite as a couple.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill explained that Grant's love for Sattler is what motivates him to get involved in the film's storyline: "He's missed her all these years, and the opportunity to spend time with Ellie Sattler…that's what really keeps Alan going.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He's happy to be with her, even if it means finding yourself in great jeopardy from time to time".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill described Grant as "a workman of few words", whereas Malcolm "never shuts up [...] and that always drives [Grant] crazy".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] However, he also considers Grant to be "quietly jealous of how cool Malcolm is", saying that whenever Malcolm is "anywhere near Ellie Sattler, he's not going to be a happy camper".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Dern, commenting on the age gap between her and Neill, said in 2022 that "it was only now, when we returned in a moment of cultural awareness about the patriarchy, that I was, like: 'Wow!
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Dern watched *Jurassic Park* again prior to filming *Jurassic World Dominion*, though Neill had not seen it since the initial press tour in 1993.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] For *Dominion*, Neill planned to prepare for the role by getting into physical shape, as the film would include running.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] One scene in particular has the cast fleeing from an animatronic dinosaur.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill, being the oldest cast member, questioned whether he could keep up with the others, though he ultimately prevailed.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill did not view Grant as an action hero, instead calling him an ordinary person thrown into extraordinary situations throughout the film series.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] In *Dominion*, Grant has brief exchanges with Owen, who previously managed to train raptors.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] According to Neill, Grant has a mixed opinion of Owen, being partially critical of his work with raptors.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He believes the two characters also have "quite a bit in common" because of their empathy with dinosaurs, while noting, "We didn't probably quite make enough of that.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] But I think it's an interesting dynamic".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill said *Dominion* would be the last *Jurassic Park* film for Dern and himself.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] However, they did reprise their roles for the *Dominion Biosyn Expansion*, another DLC pack.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] It was produced for the game *Jurassic World Evolution 2*, and was released on June 14, 2022, shortly after the theatrical release of *Dominion*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Reviewing the first film, Adam Mars-Jones of *The Independent* wrote that Grant's mistrust of technology is "the sort of quirk that a computer might come up with in a doomed attempt to give a flat character a glimmer of dimensionality".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Kenneth Turan of the *Los Angeles Times* also criticized the film, writing that "the sole point of all the carnage appears to be to increase Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant's appreciation for young people, turning him from a gruff curmudgeon into someone who has the makings of a considerate parent".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Peter Travers, writing for *Rolling Stone*, considered Neill a skilled actor but felt that he lacked the "star presence" needed to portray Grant.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] *TV Guide* wrote that the film's action elements "are not matched by its characters, acting, or dialogue.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Neill and Dern fail to achieve the larger-than-life stylization needed to register amid the effects".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Anthony Quinn of *The Independent* called *Jurassic Park III* a "hack work carried out with precision and performed with a heart", stating that Neill's "anchoring presence is always reassuring".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Derek Elley of *Variety* wrote that Grant in the third film "is largely reduced to looking worried and uttering apocalyptic warnings".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Jeff Vice of *Deseret News* found that Neill "manages to make us care about his life-or-death battle, despite his part being underwritten".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] William Arnold of the *Seattle Post-Intelligencer* wrote that Neill "is something like a movie star, and he provides a sage, comfortable, sympathetic human focus to all the mayhem".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Mashable's Kristy Puchko, in her review of *Jurassic World Dominion*, wrote that Grant is treated "like a loser who never made a life for himself out of the excavation pits".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Zoe Jordan of *Screen Rant* wrote that *Dominion* makes "the barest of efforts" to show character development in Grant.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Nick Bartlett of */Film* found Grant to be more comedic compared to the previous films.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Writing for *Observer*, Oliver Jones stated that Neill "spends much of this movie looking like a weekend warrior searching for the right aisle at Home Depot".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Some fans were disappointed by Grant and Sattler's break-up in *Jurassic Park III*, viewing it as a mistake.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] David Crow, writing for *Den of Geek*, praised *Dominion* for reuniting the two romantically, while Todd Gilchrist of *The A.V.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Club* found this aspect to be clumsily handled.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Bartlett called the reconciliation "a lovely moment for the two characters — even if it reeks of fan service".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] The character is sometimes compared to Indiana Jones, in part because they wear similar fedoras.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Tim Robey of *The Daily Telegraph* referred to Grant as "palaeontology's answer to Indiana Jones, but with a geekier hat", while Tom Chapman of *Screen Rant* wrote, "With his Harrison Ford-esque chiseled jaw, Neill forged Grant as his very own Indiana Jones, but with an added layer of sass".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Alan Grant became one of Neill's most popular roles.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He said, "What has lodged Alan Grant into people's affections is his extreme reluctance to have anything to do with children.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] He always ends up having to look after one or even two sometimes, and he does a pretty decent job.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] In 2022, Shawn Van Horn of *Collider* ranked *Jurassic Park* as Neill's most famous role, writing that while Goldblum "threatens to steal the movie in every scene he appears in, it's Neill who is the focus and the solid footing who keeps the movie feeling real, despite its unbelievable plot".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] MovieWeb's Michael Heiskell ranked the original film as Neill's best performance, and wrote that Grant's bravery throughout the series "is what makes him such an interesting character and a fan favorite".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] A shot in the first film shows Grant taking off his sunglasses, in astonishment at his first sight of a living dinosaur.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] To Neill's surprise, the shot has since become an Internet meme.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] *Jurassic Park III* includes a scene in which Grant dreams he is on an airplane with a raptor, which then speaks his name.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] Grant awakens to find it is Billy calling his name as their plane approaches Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alan-grant-jurassic-park] The talking raptor scene has also become an Internet meme.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p01] The following is a list of fictional characters from Michael Crichton's 1990 novel *Jurassic Park*, its 1995 sequel *The Lost World*, and their film adaptations, *Jurassic Park* (1993) and *The Lost World: Jurassic Park* (1997).
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p01] Also included are characters from the sequel films *Jurassic Park III*, *Jurassic World*, *Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom*, *Jurassic World Dominion*, *Jurassic World Rebirth*, and the short film *Battle at Big Rock*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p01] These films are not adaptations and have no original source novels but contain some characters and events based on the fictional universe of Crichton's novels.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p01] Some cast members from the films have also reprised their roles in certain video games.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p01] The original novel introduces several characters who would appear throughout the film series, including Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p01] *Jurassic World* introduces Owen Grady and Claire Dearing, while *Fallen Kingdom* introduces Maisie Lockwood, who are the lead characters of the *Jurassic World* trilogy.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Alan Grant is a paleontologist and the main protagonist in the first novel, as well as the first and third films.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Crichton based Grant on paleontologist Jack Horner.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Grant's research is partly focused on velociraptors.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] When the dinosaurs on Isla Nublar escape their enclosures, Grant becomes stranded in the park with Hammond's two grandchildren.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In the film adaptation, much of this period is omitted.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] For the film, several actors were considered for the part before it went to Neill, becoming one of his most popular roles.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] The film portrays Grant differently than the novel, giving him an introverted personality and a dislike of children.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] However, over the course of the first film, he warms to Hammond's grandchildren.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] The film also depicts him in a relationship with Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Ellie Sattler, who is a student of his in the novel.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] They have broken up by the time that *Jurassic Park III* takes place.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In the third film, Grant has continued his fossil research and reluctantly agrees to give an aerial tour of the dinosaurs on Isla Sorna, in exchange for dig-site financing.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He and others become stranded on the island, and Grant realizes that his new theories about raptor intelligence are correct.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In *Jurassic World Dominion*, Grant reunites with Sattler and Malcolm to investigate the giant locusts that Biosyn created.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] After Henry Wu helps out the humans in stopping the locust infestation, Grant rekindles his relationship with Sattler while planning to join Ian and Ramsay Cole in testifying against Biosyn.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Ellie Sattler is a paleobotanist who, in the novel, is a graduate student studying under Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In the film adaptation, they are a couple, and she has a more prominent role.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Sattler is one of Dern's most popular film roles.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] She briefly appears in *Jurassic Park III*, in which she and Grant have broken up, although they remain close friends.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] She is married to Mark, an employee of the U.S.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] State Department, and they have two young children.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] An early draft had featured Grant and Sattler as a couple in the process of splitting up.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In *Jurassic World Dominion*, she once again has a prominent role and is revealed to have divorced Mark by this point.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] She reunites with Grant and Malcolm to investigate the giant locusts that Biosyn created.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] After Henry Wu helps out the humans in stopping the locust infestation, Sattler rekindles her relationship with Grant while planning to join Ian and Ramsay Cole in testifying against Biosyn.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Ian Malcolm is a mathematician who specializes in chaos theory.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] His character is based on Ivar Ekeland and James Gleick.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Malcolm's all-black clothing style reflects that of Heinz-Otto Peitgen, a mathematician who wrote a richly illustrated book on fractals.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] According to Crichton, Malcolm's character functions as the "ironic commentator inside the story who talks about the action as it takes place".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Throughout the novel and film adaptation, Malcolm makes predictions based on chaos theory about the consequences and ultimate failure of attempting to control nature, which often turn out to be correct.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Malcolm is seriously injured during a *Tyrannosaurus* attack and is brought back to the Visitor Center.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Although he is declared dead at the end of the novel, he explains in the sequel, *The Lost World*, that this declaration was premature.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Malcolm is the main protagonist of *The Lost World*, in which he and others travel to Isla Sorna to conduct research about dinosaur extinction.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He is also the main protagonist of the film adaptation, titled *The Lost World: Jurassic Park*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Like the novel, Malcolm travels to Isla Sorna, but for a different reason; his girlfriend, paleontologist Sarah Harding, has already gone there to document the island's dinosaurs, and he reluctantly goes to retrieve her.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In the film series, Malcolm has several children; one of them, Kelly Curtis, appears in *The Lost World: Jurassic Park*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Malcolm has brief appearances in the 2018 film *Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom*, in which he advises against the rescue of the last surviving dinosaurs, which are threatened by an impending volcanic eruption on Isla Nublar.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Later, when the dinosaurs are dispersed globally, Malcolm reluctantly states that humans must now co-exist with them.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Malcolm returns for a larger role in the 2022 film *Jurassic World Dominion*, in which he now works for Biosyn as an in-house philosopher.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He uses his position to help Alan Grant and Ellie Sattler in exposing the company's locust scheme.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] John Hammond is the wealthy owner of Jurassic Park and founder of InGen.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He is also the grandfather to Lex and Tim Murphy.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] His antagonistic traits in the novel were removed for the film adaptation.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Although he is not modeled after anyone in particular, Crichton explained that Hammond is like the "dark side of Walt Disney".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Director Steven Spielberg described the film's Hammond as "a cross between Walt Disney and Ross Perot".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Attenborough was initially hesitant to accept the role, as he had not acted in 14 years and found film directing much easier.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He eventually accepted the part after Spielberg pleaded for him to do so, stating "I can't see anyone else playing it but you".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Near the end of the novel, Hammond falls down a hill and breaks his ankle.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He is unable to climb back up and is subsequently killed by a pack of *Procompsognathus*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] The personality of the film's Hammond is a near opposite to the novel's version, sharing only his eccentricity.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Hammond is depicted as a kind, jovial and charismatic capitalist.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Unlike the novel, he survives in the film adaptation and makes brief appearances in the second film, in which control of InGen has been taken over by his nephew Peter Ludlow.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Hammond opposes Ludlow's plan to take dinosaurs off of Isla Sorna for a new dinosaur park in San Diego, an idea that eventually fails, with Isla Sorna being declared a nature preserve.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Attenborough was to reprise his role for the fourth film, although he suffered a fall at his home in 2008 and subsequently retired from acting.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In the fourth film, *Jurassic World*, Hammond has been deceased for some time.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] A memorial statue of him is present in the new theme park known as Jurassic World.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] A viral marketing website for the fictional Masrani Global Corporation was launched to promote the film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] According to the website, Hammond died in 1997.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Simon Masrani, CEO of the Masrani Corporation and the owner of Jurassic World, is stated to have been entrusted by Hammond to direct the new park and honor Hammond's beliefs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In *Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom*, Hammond is revealed to have been partners with Benjamin Lockwood in the de-extinction of the dinosaurs, until a dispute emerges about using the same technology for human cloning, which Hammond opposes.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] A painting of Hammond appears in the film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Robert Muldoon is Jurassic Park's game warden.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He is described in the novel as a burly White Kenyan man fifty years of age, with deep blue eyes and a steel gray mustache.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In the movie he is portrayed by English actor Bob Peck.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He is a former professional hunter who worked with Hammond at one of his previous parks in Kenya.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He has experience working with dangerous predators and (unlike most other characters) his attitude toward the dinosaurs is realistic and unromantic.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He believes that the *Velociraptors* should be destroyed, describing them as smart and potentially dangerous.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He also recommended that the park be equipped with more military-grade weapons for use in emergencies, but was overruled.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He reminds Hammond of this when it dawns on them that they have no way of stopping the escaped *T. rex*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Muldoon spends most of the novel riding around the park, drinking whiskey and attempting to restore order.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He is later attacked by a pack of *Velociraptors*, but survives by wedging himself into a pipe.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He manages to kill a few of them, and eventually escapes the island with the other survivors.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In the film's introduction when a worker is attacked by a *Velociraptor* that the park staff are transporting, Muldoon gives the order to kill it.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He notes that the raptors have tested the perimeter fence in different places, probing for an opening, and comments that the animals "show extreme intelligence.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He remains in the control room with Hammond and Arnold, commenting on the many safety and security failures of the park.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] After the power failure, he drives Ellie to the *Tyrannosaurus* escape site where they rescue Malcolm.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In the jungle during an attempt to restore power, Muldoon prepares to shoot and kill a *Velociraptor* in the distance, where a second raptor ambushes him from the side while he is focused on the first raptor.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Muldoon remarks "Clever girl" as he discovers the trap and is killed by the second raptor.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] "Clever girl" would go on to become a popular quote among fans.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Donald Gennaro is a corporate attorney representing Jurassic Park's investors.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He is sent on their behalf to investigate the safety of the park after several reports of missing or dead workers.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In the novel, he is described as a short muscular man and represents an "every-man" personality among the characters.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Although he is initially worried only about disappointing his supervisors, he soon drops this concern when his life is threatened, focusing on survival instead.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] When problems begin to occur, he consistently handles them appropriately, accompanying Robert Muldoon on a mission to subdue the *Tyrannosaurus* and successfully restoring power, despite being ambushed by a *Velociraptor*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Grant claims that his negative attitude comes from trying to avoid responsibility for his role in creating the park.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Near the end of the novel, Gennaro realizes that he is partially responsible for everything occurring when Grant says: "You sold investors on an undertaking you didn't fully understand...
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] You did not check on the activities of a man whom you knew from experience to be a liar, and you permitted that man to screw around with the most dangerous technology in human history".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Gennaro then helps Grant in his attempt to wipe out the remaining *Velociraptors* and their eggs with nerve gas.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Although he survives the events on the island, he dies of dysentery sometime after.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] For the film, Spielberg condenses the characters Ed Regis and Donald Gennaro and the negative aspects of the novel's Hammond into one character.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] The result is the creation of a character whose loyalty to his employers and seriousness toward the job they gave him is easily overtaken by his own personal greed.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] When the scientists criticize Hammond's park for various reasons, Gennaro is the only one left who supports the concept, seeing great profit opportunity in the live dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Gennaro's sole negative view of the park is a $20 million lawsuit Hammond is facing from the family of a worker killed by a dinosaur at the start of the film, which becomes a decreased concern when he sees the financial potential of the park.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Gennaro is overcome by fear when the electric fence around the *Tyrannosaurus* paddock fails, and he abandons Tim and Lex.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Hiding in a toilet stall, he recites a Hail Mary and is eventually found and eaten by the *Tyrannosaurus* after she breaks out of her pen.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Prior to filming, Ferrero had suggested that his character survive but with a broken leg, swapping places with Ian Malcolm, who instead would be the one to get killed.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Henry Wu is a character in the first novel and film, and returns throughout the *Jurassic World* trilogy.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He is initially the chief geneticist at Jurassic Park and head of the team that created the dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In the novel, he is killed by a *Velociraptor*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He has a greatly reduced role in the film adaptation, but returns in a larger role for the *Jurassic World* films.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Wong believed that his diminished role in the first film was the result of "racial exclusion in Hollywood".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Colin Trevorrow and Derek Connolly, the writers of *Jurassic World*, considered Wu a logical character to return, given his role in recreating dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Wu works as the chief geneticist for the eponymous dinosaur theme park.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] He has created the genetically modified hybrid dinosaur *Indominus Rex*, which eventually escapes and wreaks havoc.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Wu is later revealed to have been secretly working with InGen Security head Hoskins to create the *Indominus* as a weapon.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In *Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom*, Wu is working for Eli Mills and has created another weaponized hybrid dinosaur, the *Indoraptor*—a scaled-down version of the *Indominus Rex*—which escapes during a dinosaur auction, killing several attendees.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Wu was knocked out during the conflict and was carried away by one of the fleeing mercenaries.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Wu also appears in the animated television series *Jurassic World Camp Cretaceous*, which reveals that he had worked on another hybrid known as *Scorpios rex*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Wu later comes back to the island with Eli Mills' henchmen to get the *Indominus rex* bone and the laptop with his hybrid research.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] However, the laptop is destroyed by the campers, later dubbed the Nublar Six, and Wu stops the mercenaries from going after them.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In *Jurassic World Dominion*, Wu is now under the employ of Biosyn and has engineered hybrid locusts using Cretaceous arthropod DNA for the company.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In an extended scene, revealed that his locusts initially engineered to spread genetic modifications on crops to improve them, but Dodgson later decided to use them to eliminate the crops of the company's rivals after the experiments failed.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] However, the scheme spirals out of control when the insects begin rapidly reproducing, threatening to lead investigators back to Biosyn.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Wu now regrets his actions and suggests that Biosyn kidnap human clone Maisie Lockwood and baby *Velociraptor* Beta, so he can study their altered DNA to spread changes to shorten their lifespan.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] From this research, Wu is able to eradicate the locust outbreak by releasing one he created with the altered DNA and gain redemption.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In *Jurassic World: Chaos Theory* season 4, taking place during the latter part of *Dominion*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Seeking to stop Biosyn's assassin dinosaur program, the Nublar Six discover that Wu is the head scientist and confront him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] To their surprise, Wu expresses remorse for his actions and asks for their help in stopping Dodgson.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Wu and the Nublar Six work together to destroy all of the data on the project -- which had been intended for training dinosaurs for search and rescue before it was twisted by Dodgson -- and put an end to the weaponization of dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] It's later mentioned that Sammy and Yaz are working with Wu and are close enough to call him "Henry," something that Darius teases them about.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Wong does not view his character as a villain but rather someone who is "extremely misguided or just in denial" about the consequences of his work.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Tim Murphy is Lex Murphy's brother and John Hammond's grandson.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In the novel, Tim is described as a bespectacled boy of about eleven who has an interest in dinosaurs and computers.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] His quick thinking and encyclopedic knowledge of dinosaurs aid the group several times, and he is instrumental in discovering that dinosaurs have escaped the island, as well as regaining the means to warn the mainland.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Later, Tim's ingenuity and technical knowledge allow him to navigate the park's computer systems and to reactivate the physical security systems before the *Velociraptors* gain access to the visitor's lodge.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] His expertise regarding dinosaurs rivals Grant's, and is superior to that of Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Wu, the scientist who created the dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Already familiar with his work before they meet, Tim almost immediately strikes up a friendship with Grant, who notes "it's hard not to like someone so interested in dinosaurs".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Tim's father does not share his interest in paleontology, so the dinosaur-loving Grant forms an instant bond with Tim during their time in the park.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In *The Lost World*, Tim is only mentioned by Ed James as starting college.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In Spielberg's film, Tim and Lex's ages are swapped and some aspects of his personality and role in the story are given to Lex.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Tim is still the child interested in dinosaurs, but all of his computer knowledge is given to Lex.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] This was done so that Spielberg could work specifically with actor Joseph Mazzello, who was younger than Ariana Richards, and to make Lex into a stronger character.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Unlike his novel counterpart, Tim does not wear spectacles in the film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Mazzello had previously screen-tested for a role in Spielberg's *Hook*, but was considered too young.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Spielberg promised to cast Mazzello in a future film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In the novel and film adaptation, Tim and Lex's parents are in the process of getting divorced.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Like Lex, Tim also makes a cameo in the second film during Ian Malcolm's visit to John Hammond, happy to see Malcolm again, but staying out of when Ian confronts Ludlow about Isla Nublar as Ian defends them from Ludlow before Hammond's butler ushers them off.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] In 2011, Mazzello told Spielberg that he wanted to reprise the role for *Jurassic Park IV*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Mazzello viewed Tim as "the obvious heir" to Hammond's fortune and Jurassic Park, and hoped that "someday we'll figure out" what happened to Tim after the events of the first film: "Would this experience have turned him away from dinosaurs and make him hate dinosaurs as a thing he once truly loved?
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p02] Alexis "Lex" Murphy is Tim Murphy's sister and John Hammond's granddaughter.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the novel, Lex is described as seven or eight years old, relatively outgoing, blonde and "a sporty young girl who loves baseball".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] She wears a baseball glove slung over her shoulder and a baseball cap just about everywhere.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Lex is shown to have the traits of a stereotypical child that often complains.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Her behavior often annoys the people around her and puts her and the group in danger.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Throughout the novel, she shows characteristics of Hammond, such as being careless and unappreciative of the events occurring around her, though not evil.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In *The Lost World*, her character is said to be starting college-preparatory school.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In Spielberg's 1993 film, Lex is the older of the two siblings, aged 12–14, and has a personality similar to her brother's from the novel.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the film, Lex has advanced computer skills that help the survivors escape a pack of *Velociraptors*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] While initially frightened by many of the dinosaurs, Lex eventually gains courage and is instrumental in rebooting the park's systems.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Lex's character was strengthened, like Ellie Sattler, to add strong female roles to the film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Richards was happy with the sibling age swap, as she found the novel version of Lex to be an "annoying brat".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In auditioning for the role, Richards said: "I was called into a casting office, and they just wanted me to scream.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] I heard later on that Steven had watched a few girls on tape that day, and I was the only one who ended up waking his sleeping wife on the couch, and she came running through the hallway to see if the kids were all right".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Spielberg was also impressed by her role in the 1992 film *Timescape*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Richards performed most of her own stunts in *Jurassic Park*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Christina Ricci was among those who had auditioned for the role.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Lex makes a cameo in the second film when Ian Malcolm comes to visit Hammond.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] She briefly listens to Malcolm as he argues with Ludlow regarding what happened on Isla Nublar, defending her and Tim when Ludlow tries to drag them into the argument, before Hammond's butler ushers them off.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] The character has not returned and has not been mentioned in subsequent films.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] An early draft of *Jurassic Park IV* featured Lex in a small role, with Keira Knightley in consideration to play the part.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Richards was not asked to reprise her role for the *Jurassic World* films, but remained open to eventually returning.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] John Arnold is Jurassic Park's chief engineer, running the main control center from the Visitor Center.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is described as a thin chain-smoker and chronic worrier.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] A gifted systems engineer, Arnold had designed weapons for the U.S. military, and later worked at several theme parks and zoos before joining the Jurassic Park team.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is a grudgingly optimistic man, who maintains total faith in the computer systems and continues to believe that despite the setbacks, things will eventually work out.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] When Dennis Nedry locks them out of the system, Arnold, after much persuasion by Donald Gennaro, shuts off all power to the park and resets the computer-control systems.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] After turning the power back on, he believes the problem has been solved, when it has actually been made worse.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] The reset has left the park running only on auxiliary power and disabled the electric fences around the dinosaur paddocks, allowing the creatures to break free.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Upon realizing his mistake, Arnold volunteers to go to the power plant and restart the main generator; before he can accomplish this task, he is killed by an escaped *Velociraptor*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In Spielberg's 1993 film, Arnold is referred to as "Ray", instead of John, to distinguish him from John Hammond.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] However, in a deleted scene from the second film, he is mentioned as "John Arnold".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the film, Arnold has a smaller role than in the novel but retains the same personality and outlook, often prefacing a risky action with the comment, "Hold on to your butts".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Arnold's death is not shown on camera, but is confirmed when his severed arm falls onto Ellie's shoulder in the power shed.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Arnold's line "Hold on to your butts" has become a popular quote.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] The film's writer, David Koepp, had been on the set for *Death Becomes Her* (1992), another film he wrote.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] That film's director, Robert Zemeckis, said "Hold onto your butts" while reviewing dailies, and Koepp decided to add the line into *Jurassic Park*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Jackson was intended to film a lengthy death scene in Hawaii, in which his character is chased and killed by raptors, but the set for this scene was destroyed by Hurricane Iniki.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dennis Nedry is one of the main human antagonists in the novel and film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the novel, he is described as an very skinny, messy and an increasingly obnoxious computer scientist.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Nedry works for Hammond as the system's programmer and is in charge of networking Jurassic Park's computers.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Although he was not given any details about InGen's operation, Nedry was expected to fix numerous bugs and issues without understanding the ultimate goal.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] After InGen requires him to make changes to the system without further payment, he strikes a deal with Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson of Biosyn to steal embryos of the park's 15 dinosaur species.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Nedry is promised $50,000 for each species he delivers, and an additional $50,000 for each embryo that proves viable, for a maximum payment of $1.5 million.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson provides Nedry with an embryo carrier/cooler disguised as a can of shaving cream.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Nedry records their conversation, intending to enclose a copy with the embryos as a reminder of their agreement.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In order to carry out the theft, he shuts down the park's security systems, including several electric fences surrounding select dinosaur paddocks.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He plans to steal embryos from a secure lab, drive across the park to hand them off to a Biosyn agent waiting at the dock, and then return to the control room and reactivate the security systems before his absence becomes suspicious.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] On his way to deliver the embryos, a tropical storm causes him to miss crucial road signs, and he becomes lost in the jungle.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is subsequently blinded and killed by a venomous *Dilophosaurus*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the novel, his body is later found by Muldoon and Gennaro.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Nedry's intricate, complex computer knowledge makes him vain and prideful, but later, one of Hammond's grandchildren is able to navigate Nedry's system and restore power to the Visitor Center.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Nedry's role in the film is generally the same as in the novel, with some minor changes to his fate.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He crashes his Jeep through a guardrail and runs off the road, then takes shelter in the vehicle after a *Dilophosaurus* spits venom in his eyes, dropping the shaving cream container as a result.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] The animal rears up in the passenger seat, after which the camera cuts to a long shot of the Jeep shaking to the sound of Nedry's screams.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] His body and the container are not found by anyone, the latter rolling down a hill and becoming buried in mud.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the second film, Nedry's death is not mentioned, neither in the general release nor in a deleted scene in which Ludlow mentions the names of deceased victims to InGen's board of directors.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In *Jurassic World: Camp Cretaceous*, while hunting for Blue the *Velociraptor*, Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson accidentally finds and retrieves the canister containing the embryos that Nedry had stolen for him, commenting that he could have used them 25 years before.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In *Jurassic World Dominion*, when Dodgson's scheme is exposed, he flees and takes the canister with him, only to be killed by three *Dilophosaurus* in an attack mirroring Nedry's fate.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Knight was cast in the role after Spielberg saw his performance in *Basic Instinct* (1992).
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Knight described the film shoot as a "miserable" experience: "I'm sliding down things, I've got mud all over me, I'm soaking wet, I'm 5 billion pounds, I can barely walk.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Nedry's wardrobe in the film is similar to clothing worn by several characters in another Spielberg film, *The Goonies* (1985), leading to speculation that his attire is a reference to the earlier film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In *Jurassic Park: The Game* which is set immediately after the events of the first film, the characters Miles Chadwick and Nima Cruz discover Nedry's body.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In *Lego Jurassic World: The Secret Exhibit* and *Lego Jurassic World: Legend of Isla Nublar*, Dennis is revealed to have a nephew named Danny Nedermeyer who makes repeated efforts to sabotage Jurassic World in honor of his uncle.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] It is also revealed that Dennis was searching for the lost treasure of the pirate Captain No-Beard which was said to be buried somewhere on Isla Nublar.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Harding is Jurassic Park's chief veterinarian.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the novel, he had been the chief of veterinary medicine for the San Diego Zoo, and was the world's leading expert on avian care.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He accepted the job at Jurassic Park because he wanted to become famous for writing the first textbook on the care of dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] When the group first encounters him, he is caring for an ill *Stegosaurus*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] With the help of Ellie, he finds the source of the animal's sickness and is able to treat it.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Being the only medical doctor on the island, he treats Malcolm's injuries.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is attacked by a *Velociraptor* during the assault on the Visitor Center, but ultimately survives his time on the island.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] It is implied in the second novel that Sarah Harding is his daughter.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He makes a brief appearance in the first film with a sick *Triceratops*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is portrayed by the film's producer, Jerry Molen.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] The character's first name is never mentioned in the novel or the film, although he is referred to as Gerry Harding in *The Making of Jurassic Park*, which chronicles the film's production.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He appears as one of the main characters in *Jurassic Park: The Game*, a 2011 film-inspired video game in which he has a daughter named Jess.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Gerry Harding in the game, and is portrayed as being significantly younger than in the film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Sarah Harding is mentioned as his other daughter, something also acknowledged in the 2015 game *Lego Jurassic World*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Lewis Dodgson is the main antagonist of both the *Jurassic Park* novels, and the main antagonist in *Jurassic World Dominion* as well as an antagonist in *Jurassic World: Camp Cretaceous* and *Jurassic World: Chaos Theory*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the novels, Dodgson is an ambitious geneticist who is unafraid to make aggressive moves, generally considered unethical, to achieve his goals.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He states that he "won't be held back by regulations made for lesser souls".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson works for the Biosyn Corporation, a company that rivals Hammond's but has a far spottier scientific reputation.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson is described in the novels as more of a salesman than a scientist, and someone who specializes in both reverse engineering and stealing the work of others.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In his past as a graduate student, he had been dismissed by Johns Hopkins University for attempting a gene therapy experiment on human patients without following the proper Food and Drug Administration (FDA) protocols.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Notably, in 1986, he recklessly experimented on an untested vaccine against neurotropic viruses on a farm in Chile, which mutated a strain into an airborne disease.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] However, due to technicalities, Dodgson escaped justice and he remains working at Biosyn.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He hopes to get his hands on Hammond's technology in order to create dinosaurs of his own.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He and Biosyn seek to clone dinosaurs not as an attraction, but as potential test subjects for laboratory applications.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is portrayed as cold and ruthless, yet patient and practical, preferring to operate in the shadows with no one suspecting him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the first novel, Dodgson hires Dennis Nedry to steal dinosaur embryos for Biosyn, but the plot fails when Nedry is killed by a *Dilophosaurus* on his way to deliver the embryos.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the sequel novel, Dodgson is a much more ambitious, villainous, and antagonistic character.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Prior to the novel's events, Dodgson test-marketed a crop of genetically altered potatoes that ended up hospitalizing children after eating them.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] However, he still manages to evade the law by bribing officials.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He takes a team to Isla Sorna in an attempt to collect fertilized dinosaur eggs, during which he tried to murder Sarah Harding.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Ignorant of the dangers of these animals, Dodgson and his team are killed, with Dodgson being consumed by an infant *Tyrannosaurus* after being captured by one of the adults.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Biosyn is not mentioned in the first film, and Dodgson only makes a short appearance when he meets Nedry in San Jose, Costa Rica, and gives him $750,000 and an embryo transfer device disguised as a shaving cream container.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson's brief appearance has inspired a number of fan recreations and musical remixes on YouTube, usually featuring a line from Nedry: "We've got Dodgson here!" For the second film, Dodgson is replaced by the character Peter Ludlow.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In *Jurassic World Camp Cretaceous*, Dodgson, now the head of research for Biosyn, travels to Isla Nublar to make a deal with Daniel Kon for mind control chips for the dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson seeks to control the dinosaurs and show the world that the problem was Masrani and Hammond rather than the creatures themselves.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] With the help of Kenji Kon, Dodgson seeks to capture several dinosaurs, including Blue the *Velociraptor*, but he is nearly killed by a pack of *Dilophosaurus* before being saved by Daniel.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the process, Dodgson inadvertently stumbles across and retrieves the canister containing the embryos that Nedry had stolen for him twenty-five years before.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Pleased with the success of their mission, Dodgson finalizes his deal with Daniel, but Laura Molina, one of his investors, attempts to make off with Dodgson's pack containing Biosyn's entire prospectus and the canister.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Kenji manages to stop her and retrieve the pack and Molina is eaten by a pack of Compys.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Before departing the island, Dodgson asks for DNA samples from the Nublar dinosaurs as well so that Biosyn can clone their own dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] However, Mae Turner turns on Mantah Corp and destroys her samples while Kenji and his friends sabotage Mantah Corp's operations, preventing them from completing their deal with Dodgson.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson returns in *Jurassic World: Chaos Theory* season 3 which partially runs concurrent with the events of *Dominion*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Now the CEO of Biosyn Genetics, he partners with Soyona Santos' dinosaur smuggling operation.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson is revealed to secretly be behind the dinosaur black market seen in *Dominion* as well as an *Atrociraptor* pack terrorizing a university professor and UN advisor.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson has been working to get Biosyn dominion over all dinosaurs on Earth which the man had opposed.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson advocates killing an Italian Regional Counsellor who is holding up the special land permit for Biosyn Valley, but he seemingly concedes to Santos' argument for intimidation instead.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] However, Dodgson promptly goes behind her back to hire the *Atrociraptor* Handler to kill the man anyways.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Although infuriated, Santos chooses to keep quiet due to the greater payoff of getting ownership of the market.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson tasks Santos and Brooklynn with capturing Maisie Lockwood and Blue's daughter Beta for him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Brooklynn—who recognizes Dodgson from his dealings with Mantah Corp years before—convinces Santos that he can't be trusted and goes undercover in the market to find out more information on Dodgson's activities.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] After the black market is destroyed during a raid by French Intelligence, Owen Grady and Claire Dearing (as seen in *Dominion*), Santos contacts Dodgson for an extraction and he sends her a drone helicopter to take Santos to Biosyn.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] However, Santos' escape is foiled by Brooklynn, Darius, Ben and Yaz and she is arrested by Barry Sembène and French Intelligence.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Following Santos' arrest, Brooklynn, Darius, Ben and Yaz take Santos' escape helicopter to Biosyn to stop Dodgson once and for all while their friends Kenji and Sammy—the same group who had stopped Dodgson's plans with Mantah Corp—make their way to Biosyn to rescue the *Ankylosaurus* Bumpy.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In season 4, Kenji blackmails Dodgson by threatening to expose his crimes to the media to get him to lead Kenji and Sammy to Bumpy.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In a rare moment of open honesty, Dodgson explains to Kenji that he sees his work as a scientific Fountain of Youth aimed at bettering the world.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson betrays the two in an attempt to get rid of them rather than actually leading Kenji and Sammy to Bumpy.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] At the same time, the others sneak into Biosyn and confront a remorseful Henry Wu.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Wu explains that he had intended to train the dinosaurs for search and rescue, but Dodgson had twisted his research to create the assassin dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] With the help of Wu, the Nublar Six destroy Biosyn's research into weaponizing dinosaurs, putting an end to it.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] While trying to escape from Biosyn, Darius sees Dodgson boarding a hyperloop on a security camera.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Shortly thereafter, the power goes out, and Dodgson is devoured by a *Dilophosaurus* pack that had entered the hyperloop tunnel in pursuit of Ben and Kenji.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In *Dominion*, Dodgson has worked his way up to become CEO of Biosyn Genetics.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] With dinosaurs now roaming among humans, Dodgson led Biosyn in capturing dinosaurs and placing them in a sanctuary at the company's headquarters in Italy's Dolomites mountain range.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] The company conducts research on the dinosaurs to potentially advance medical research.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson has also taken to keeping the shaving cream canister that he gave to Nedry in his office on his trophy shelf.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is publicly seen as an awkward but inspiring leader with his appeal helping Biosyn recruit several idealistic young people under his employ.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] However, he is secretly still nefarious and business-minded, having hired Henry Wu to engineer a breed of transgenic locusts that consume the crops of rival companies and Soyona Santos to serve as a criminal liaison to the black markets and for other off-the-books activities.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In an extended scene, revealed that the locusts initially designed to spread genetic modifications on crops to give them defenses against diseases, harsh climates, and pests.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] After the experiments failed, instead of destroying the locusts, Dodgson decided to use them to eliminate rival crops.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Alan Grant and Ellie Sattler arrive at Biosyn's headquarters to investigate the company's connection with the locusts, which are stored in a room at the facility.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson fires Ian Malcolm, the company's in-house philosopher, after learning that he helped Grant and Sattler in their investigation.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He sets the insects on fire to destroy evidence, but they break free and set the surrounding forest on fire, burning the facility and further exposing him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Before leaving Biosyn, Malcolm exposes Dodgson's actions to his employees.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] While preparing to flee, Dodgson assures his close aide, Ramsay Cole, that they can rebuild.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is stunned to learn that Ramsay has also been working to expose him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson flees through Biosyn's hyperloop, taking the canister with him, although he is killed by three *Dilophosaurus*, just like Nedry, after Ellie and Claire Dearing cut power to the hyperloop.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] After his death, Dodgson's reputation is posthumously ruined by the revelation of his crimes and his company is at risk of going to defunct, starting with the United Nations taking over the protection rights of the dinosaurs from Biosyn.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In 2013, Thor expressed enthusiasm in reprising the role, if asked to return, but he was convicted of sexual assault in 2015 and sentenced to six years in prison.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In *Dominion*, Campbell Scott took over the role.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Director and co-writer Colin Trevorrow was interested in bringing the character back after his brief appearance in *Jurassic Park*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the years after the first film, Trevorrow envisioned Dodgson as having worked his way up to become CEO of Biosyn.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He described Dodgson as someone who "is a mentor to others and yet is betraying all of them by betraying their values".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] To prepare for the role, Scott watched the previous *Jurassic Park* films and also read Crichton's novels, as he wanted to incorporate elements of Crichton's character into the film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He found that the books sometimes portray Dodgson as "just a plain sociopath", which he wanted to avoid in *Dominion*, stating, "It's much more interesting to play a sociopath who has a lot of depth and has interesting intentions behind their actions".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Speaking about his role in *Dominion*, Scott said that Dodgson "will do anything to get people out of his way, or on his side, depending on who he meets".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] DNA is a cartoon character that resembles an anthropomorphic DNA helix with a face and arms.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is the mascot for InGen and the theme parks Jurassic Park and Jurassic World.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Most of his lines and explanations are said by Henry Wu in the novel during a tour of the genetics lab, some of which is still given to the cameo Wu makes in the original film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] DNA appears in videos to help visitors understand the processes involved in the creation of the dinosaurs at Jurassic Park (the character itself was created for the film for virtually the same reasons, to provide exposition for the film's audience).
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] A video starring him and InGen's founder John Hammond is played in a theater located in the park's Visitor Center before a tour.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] For the film adaptation, Spielberg and writer David Koepp had faced difficulty in explaining the novel's scientific elements, until Spielberg devised the idea of an animated character who would inform the audience and characters.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Koepp believed the idea went well with the theme park setting.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Bob Kurtz developed the animation sequence.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] DNA became a popular character among fans.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the Super NES version of the *Jurassic Park* video game, Mr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] DNA appears onscreen and offers the player dinosaur trivia.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the 2011 video game *Jurassic Park: The Game* by Telltale Games, Mr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] DNA is visible on the maintenance board of Jurassic Park's geothermal power plant and on a board indicating how tall a person must be to ride the upcoming Bone Shaker roller coaster.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] DNA was used by the Masrani Global Corporation for their new dinosaur park Jurassic World which became an improvement of Jurassic World.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Visitors encounter him in the Innovation Center where he explains the basics of genetics and how the dinosaurs were recreated.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] The character's original voice actor Greg Burson died in 2008.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] *Jurassic World* director Colin Trevorrow provided the voice for the new film and said "it actually happened by mistake – I did it once in a booth, we were at a sound mix studio and I just [threw] it in there and we decided to keep it".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Some effects were used to alter Trevorrow's voice, making him sound like Burson.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the 2015 video game *Lego Jurassic World*, Mr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] DNA is a playable character and also appears throughout the game to give hints to the player(s) on how to progress through the levels.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] As with the original *Jurassic Park* video game, he also offers the player(s) dinosaur trivia.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is aware of InGen's political dealings and will inform the player of them, yet always presents such in a positive way.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] DNA also appears in the first season and the interactive special of *Jurassic World Camp Cretaceous*, voiced by Jeff Bergman.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Ed Regis is a publicist for InGen and the head of public relations for Jurassic Park.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Regis is often given odd jobs by Hammond that are outside his area of expertise, such as escorting a wounded worker to a Costa Rican hospital, and acting as a babysitter for Lex and Tim during their visit to the park.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Despite being overconfident about the park and almost negligent about the accidents that have been occurring, fear quickly overtakes him as things begin to go wrong, since he had already witnessed the brutality of dinosaur attacks.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] When the *Tyrannosaurus* breaks free of its pen, he abandons the tour vehicle, leaving Tim and Lex behind.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] After hiding between some boulders, he tries to make his way back to the cars, but is killed by a juvenile *Tyrannosaurus*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] His severed leg is later discovered by Gennaro and Muldoon as they investigate the attack.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Ed Regis's character is written out of the film, although certain aspects of his character such as his nervousness and cowardice are given to the film's version of Donald Gennaro.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Gennaro's death sequence during the *T. rex* attack in the film is reminiscent of Regis's death.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Marty Gutierrez is an American biologist who lives in Costa Rica.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He plays an expository role in both novels.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the first novel, he identifies an unknown lizard that attacks a little girl as *Basiliscus amoratus*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is initially unhappy with this identification because the lizard was more venomous than expected and had three toes.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He searches the beach where she was attacked and finds the corpse of a similar lizard in the mouth of a howler monkey; he promptly sends the body for laboratory analysis.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He also appears at the end of the novel, when the survivors are being held back for questioning by the Costa Rican government.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Grant that the survivors, with the exception of the children, will not be leaving any time soon.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the second novel, he befriends and shows Richard Levine the desiccated corpse of an unknown creature, oddly similar to the ones found prior to the Jurassic Park incident.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He informs Levine that no one knows where these creatures are coming from, and the two argue about whether or not these are dinosaur remains.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Gutierrez misidentifies the carcass while Levine identifies it as an *Ornitholestes*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Gutierrez is the only character to appear in both novels but none of the films.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Crichton wrote a sequel novel, *The Lost World*, which was published in 1995.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Spielberg returned to direct a film adaptation, released as *The Lost World: Jurassic Park* in 1997.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In both the novel and film, two teams travel to Isla Sorna, a second island of dinosaurs that served as the breeding site before moving the animals to Isla Nublar.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] While one team intends to observe the dinosaurs, the other attempts to take them off the island and exploit them for profit.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Like its predecessor, the film adaptation omits certain characters while adding new ones.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Sarah Harding is an ethologist who specializes in African predators.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] She is depicted as dark-haired and muscular.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] She is intelligent, feisty and rugged, and employs common sense and practicality in dangerous situations, putting the safety of her colleagues first.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Her calm personality permits her to quickly take command of the group and devise ways for them to survive and escape Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Ian Malcolm were in a relationship for a period, and at one point she claimed she was in love with him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] The relationship did not work out, although they remained close friends.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] She is idolized by Kelly Curtis who sees her as tough and smart.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the novel, she mentions that her father was a veterinarian and bird specialist at the San Diego Zoo, implying that Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] She rides a motorcycle on several occasions, including an instance where she is being chased by raptors.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Harding travels to Isla Sorna with Lewis Dodgson and his group, believing them to be friends of Malcolm.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] As they approach the island, Dodgson throws Harding overboard to avoid possible interference in his plan to steal dinosaur eggs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Later, Harding and Dodgson take cover from a *Tyrannosaurus* under an SUV, and she pushes him out to be snatched by the dinosaur.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the film, Harding's character is merged with that of Richard Levine's.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] She is intelligent and feisty as well as kind and jolly, but impulsive and too eager to interact with the animals, often placing herself and others in danger.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] As well, her character is a behavioral paleontologist rather than just an animal behaviorist, who specializes in dinosaur parenting behavior.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Her relationship with Malcolm is more in-depth, as they had gotten together after the events of the first film and remain together throughout the second.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Moore was not asked to return for any sequels, but she expressed an interest in reprising the role.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Roland Tembo is a hunter hired by InGen to lead its expedition on Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] His primary motivation for going to the island is so he and Ajay Sidhu, his hunting partner and close friend, can hunt the ultimate trophy, a male *Tyrannosaurus*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Although he gets his prize in the end, he is devastated by the death of Ajay.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] When Ludlow offers him a job at the planned Jurassic Park attraction in San Diego, he declines by saying: "I believe I've spent enough time in the company of death".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Without hesitation, Roland leaves the island by helicopter.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] David Koepp, the film's writer, chose the name Roland as a reference to one of his favorite songs, "Roland the Headless Thompson Gunner", by Warren Zevon.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Spielberg wanted to work with Postlethwaite after seeing his performance in the 1993 film *In the Name of the Father*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Postlethwaite described Roland as an "ambivalent" character rather than a villain, noting that he "has a sort of mind change before the end and realizes that what Ludlow is up to is not particularly wholesome".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Peter Ludlow is the main antagonist of the second film, John Hammond's nephew, and the newly elected CEO of InGen.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He attained this position after convincing InGen's board of directors to oust Hammond following an accident on Isla Sorna, in which a group of *Compsognathus* attacked a girl who was visiting the island with her family.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Ludlow is also directly responsible for tarnishing Ian Malcolm's reputation, through outright bribes to Costa Rican officials and misinformation to the press, when Malcolm tries to expose InGen's cover-up of the Jurassic Park incident.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] His character is ruthless, selfish, greedy and condescending toward those who work for him or those he dislikes.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] As a result, he is not well respected by the members of his team who instead choose to follow Roland Tembo or Nick Van Owen.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In an attempt to revitalize Hammond's original Jurassic Park attraction in San Diego, Ludlow assembles an InGen team to recover Isla Sorna's dinosaurs and move them to the original park.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] But Ludlow only manages to bring back the male *T. rex* and his infant, with disastrous results leading to his own demise as the adult *T. rex* wreaks havoc on San Diego.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Ludlow takes the place of Lewis Dodgson, the main antagonist of the novel.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] While trying to recapture the infant in the hold of an InGen cargo ship, he is confronted and captured by the adult and then fed to the infant.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Whereas Hammond had learned from his mistakes in the first film, Ludlow remains out of touch with reality, failing to understand that a dinosaur theme park simply doesn't work and sees only the money in the dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Nick Van Owen is a video documentarian and member of Malcolm's expedition to Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is an experienced field photographer who has covered wildlife and combat situations, and began volunteering with Greenpeace to meet women.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] His experience with Greenpeace later spurs him to act in defense of the dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is the only member of his team to be warned by Hammond about InGen's expedition, and sneaks into their camp to release captured animals and disrupt their harvesting operation.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He also rescues the infant *T. rex* from Roland Tembo, leading to a confrontation with its parents which strands both teams on the island.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] As the teams merge and form an escape plan, Nick easily gains the tacit respect of the rugged InGen men, as in one scene he is shown to effortlessly motivate the men while Peter Ludlow fails.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] His activist nature conflicts with the hunter style of Roland, and he covertly switches the latter's ammunition to ensure the *T. rex* adults will not be killed.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] When the group reaches the island's InGen compound, Nick uses the radio to call for rescue.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He leaves on the first evacuation helicopter departing Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] As with Roland, Koepp chose the surname Van Owen as a reference to one of his favorite songs, "Roland the Headless Thompson Gunner", by Warren Zevon.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Vaughn was cast after Spielberg saw his performance in an early cut of *Swingers*, whose filmmakers had asked for Spielberg's permission to use music from his earlier film *Jaws*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Kelly Curtis is a close friend of Arby in the novel, and is Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the novel, Kelly is a 13-year-old girl who is fascinated by science and idolizes Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Kelly's teacher Richard Levine, aware that he is being followed by Ed James, hires her and Arby as his assistants to run errands for him ahead of his expedition to Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] When Kelly learns that Sarah will be on the trip, she and Arby decide to sneak aboard a trailer being transported to the island.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] While there, Kelly manages to shoot a *Velociraptor* with a specialized rifle with venom darts, and a second raptor, saving Levine.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] She later helps Sarah rescue their motorcycle from another raptor and locate a service tunnel, allowing the survivors to escape from the attacking raptors.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] The film adaptation portrays her as African-American, a trait shared by Arby, who is omitted from the movie, thereby making the film version of Kelly a composite character.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the film, Kelly was abandoned by her mother after her parents separated, and she has a strained relationship with her father Malcolm.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] She uses her gymnastics skills to rescue her father from a *Velociraptor*, by swinging on a pipe and eventually kicking the dinosaur out a window.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] The gymnastics scene is often criticized.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Chester was cast after director Steven Spielberg met her at the premiere of her 1995 film *A Little Princess*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] The film's writer, David Koepp, initially wrote Kelly as a student of Malcolm's, although Koepp found it difficult to make this idea work.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He later suggested that Kelly be written as Ian's daughter, although he and Spielberg initially doubted this due to differing skin colors, but they eventually proceeded with the idea.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Chester said: "I was surprised, but I really didn't care.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] I just thought: Well, I guess I'm an interracial kid in a movie.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Koepp wanted to write an explanation into the script regarding the characters' difference in skin color, but he could not think of a simple way to address it.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Jeff Goldblum, who portrays Malcolm, liked "the way it's not even explained and kind of just accepted.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] The interracial aspect is only briefly acknowledged when Nick asks Eddie if he sees a family resemblance between the two.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Goldblum briefly returns as Malcolm in *Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom*, although there were never any plans to bring Kelly back for the film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Speculating on Malcolm's relationship with Kelly, Goldblum said at the time: "I've imagined that the two of us have become even closer, and I supported all her empowerment and freedom and glorious talents".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dieter Stark is Roland Tembo's second-in-command during the InGen team's expedition on Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dieter expresses dislike for Nick Van Owen and gets into a scuffle with him following Nick's release of the InGen team's captured dinosaurs, who destroyed the team's base camp and communications equipment.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He gets lost in the forest while looking for a spot to urinate, and is attacked and killed by a group of *Compsognathus*, similar to Hammond in the first novel.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Ajay Sidhu is an African hunter of Indian descent who is Roland Tembo's friend and hunting partner.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He accompanies Roland during his attempt to capture the *T. rex*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] While he and the InGen team flee from the *T. rex* to take refuge in a derilict InGen compound in Isla Sorna, the latter enters an elephant grass field, wherein he shouts at them to avoid the place; the team disobeys this warning, after which he follows them in.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] The group is then killed by *Velociraptors* hiding in the grass.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Ajay's death is not shown on screen, but Roland later confirms it by stating that Ajay "didn't make it".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Six actors were considered for the role.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Gopakumar was initially cast as Ajay, but soon had to drop out of the project, because of trouble acquiring a work visa in time for filming.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Eddie Carr is the key assistant to Doc Thorne.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is added to the team because the vehicles he help designed have not been field-tested.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Eddie is frightened by Isla Sorna and wants nothing more than to retrieve Richard Levine and get off the island as soon as possible.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Ian Malcolm does not like that Eddie's life is so heavily influenced by unreliable electronics.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] When a pack of raptors attack the high hide, they yank him off and kill him, before dragging his body to their nest.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the novel, he is described as a compact and strong 25-year-old who prefers life in the city.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the film, he has dark brown hair, is balding, and is at least ten years older than the description in the novel, taking on some characteristics of Jack Thorne.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the film, while trying to rescue Ian, Sarah, and Nick, he is ripped in half by two adult *T. rex* before they push the trailers off the cliff.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Malcolm demands that he be given respect for trying to save them.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Schiff had initially auditioned for *High Incident*, a television series that was executive-produced by Spielberg.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] After viewing his audition tape, Spielberg decided to cast him in *The Lost World*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] While filming, Spielberg came to like the character so much, he considered keeping him alive for the film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] However, Schiff convinced Spielberg to go on with the death scene: "I went, 'Well, no, I think it's better to kill me off, because then all bets are off.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] If you like my character, then Jeff Goldblum might be next.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Robert Burke is the InGen team's paleontologist who provides several pieces of incorrect information.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] During a conversation with Malcolm, Sarah Harding states, "Robert Burke said that the *T. rex* was a rogue that would abandon its young at the earliest opportunity".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Burke's theory is disproved later in the film when adult *Tyrannosaurs* attack the trailer in which their infant is being held.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Burke and others hide behind a waterfall when they are pursued by a *Tyrannosaurus*, but he is startled when a milk snake slithers down into his shirt.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He panics and is subsequently caught and eaten by the *T. rex*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Burke is based on the paleontologist Robert Bakker, and Duffy consulted with Bakker to prepare for the role.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Richard Levine is one of the most brilliant and wealthy paleontologists in the *Jurassic Park* universe.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] His wealth comes from a series of dolls produced by a company that he inherited.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] While researching potential dinosaur sightings, he befriends Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Levine's egotism and spontaneous personality prove to be a source of constant irritation to the rest of his colleagues, especially Malcolm and Thorne.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] After being arrested for speeding, Levine is ordered by a judge to teach a junior high school class, where he meets students Arby Benton and Kelly Curtis.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Aware that he is being followed by Ed James, Levine hires Arby and Kelly as his assistants to run errands for him ahead of the expedition.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Levine originally intended to travel to Isla Sorna as part of Malcolm's team, but goes there on his own before the Costa Rican government has a chance to destroy the island.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] When the rest of his team arrives, they find themselves constantly running after him when he decides to continue his research regardless of what is happening around him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is bitten twice by *Procompsognathus*, but ultimately escapes the island without major harm.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Levine does not appear in the film adaptation, and some of his traits are instead given to Sarah Harding.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Jack "Doc" Thorne is a former university professor of applied engineering from Stanford who specializes in building field equipment, vehicles, and weaponry for field scientists.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He exhibits an eclectic mix of character traits, relying on both practical expertise and Eastern philosophy, claiming that one needs to know philosophy and history to succeed in engineering.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] His company, Thorne Mobile Field Systems, is hired to outfit Richard Levine's expedition to Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Thorne's contribution to Levine's mission includes a large research trailer, nicknamed "The Challenger", an electric SUV, a motor bike, a pair of air rifles with poisonous darts, and a modified satellite phone.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] When Levine goes missing on the island, Thorne heads to Isla Sorna with Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Ian Malcolm and Eddie Carr to rescue him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Thorne saves his colleague multiple times, and survives his time on the island.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] In the novel, he is depicted as caring for the children Kelly Curtis and Arby Benton.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Thorne is not in the film, although parts of his character are integrated into the roles of Eddie Carr and Roland Tembo.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] "Arby" Benton is an 11-year-old African-American boy who is good friends with Kelly.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is easily frightened, and tends to be quiet and shy, but is very intelligent and an expert with computers.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He skipped two school grades and is in seventh grade with Kelly.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] When Kelly expressed interest in stowing away in the Challenger trailer with him, it was Arby who came up with a plan on how to do so.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] At one point, he becomes trapped in a predator-proof cage which is pushed away by velociraptors toward their nest.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] As a result, he suffers lost teeth, and bruises and cuts.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He does not appear in the film adaptation, although Kelly is portrayed in the film as an African American (thereby making her a composite character).
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Once a successful biologist employed by Biosyn, he lost credibility when his research on blood-coagulation factors failed.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson hired King as his assistant in the reverse-engineering department.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is divorced and has one child, who he sees only on weekends.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He accompanies Dodgson to the island, and eventually begins to disagree with Dodgson's dark desires such as the attempted drowning of Sarah Harding.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] They are separated after being chased by *Tyrannosaurs*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Eventually, King flees from a pack of raptors in a field of tall grass.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] A *Velociraptor* knocks him over and inserts its claws into his back, before biting into his neck and killing him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Other raptors soon join to devour his body.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] George Baselton is a biology professor and assistant to Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is characterized as a "celebrity biologist".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] As a well known authority and pundit, he is retained by Biosyn and Dodgson to spin any bad press that may arise.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] When he, Howard King and Dodgson try to steal *Tyrannosaurus* eggs, the sonic device Dodgson is using to keep the parent *Tyrannosaurs* at bay becomes unplugged.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Dodgson and Baselton stand still, believing a paleontological article which theorized that the dinosaur's vision is based on movement.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] This turns out to be false, and the *Tyrannosaurus* eats Baselton alive.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is a young and enthusiastic Costa Rican who visited the island several times as a boy and knows it well.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] When Levine warns him to be quiet, he simply says that they have nothing to fear.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He seems to annoy Levine many times, not only with his insistence that only birds live on the island, but also by disobeying his orders to refrain from using items like cigarettes and making noise.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Diego is ambushed and killed by a *Carnotaurus* while he and Levine watch a *Mussaurus* in total awe.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He has a cousin named Gandoca who takes Dodgson, King, Baselton, and Harding on a boat trip to Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Ed James is a private investigator hired by Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Lewis Dodgson to get information about Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] Richard Levine and the survivors of the Isla Nublar incident.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He is uncomfortable around Dodgson due to his temper and reputation.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] After placing a bug in Levine's apartment, he learns the location of Isla Sorna and reports it to Dodgson.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p03] He does not accompany either team to the island.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] These characters only appear in the third film, *Jurassic Park III* (2001), as there is no third novel.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] In the film, 12-year-old Eric Kirby goes missing while parasailing near Isla Sorna, also known as Site B.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The Costa Rican and U.S. governments decline to search for Eric.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] His divorced parents, Paul and Amanda Kirby, pose as a wealthy couple and offer to finance Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Alan Grant's dig site if he accompanies them to the island and provides an aerial tour of its dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] In reality, the Kirbys plan to look for their son with Grant's help.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The group become stranded and encounter numerous dinosaurs, including a *Spinosaurus*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The Kirbys' mercenary team is killed, and Grant's graduate student Billy steals *Velociraptor* eggs to secure funding, putting the survivors at further risk when the raptors begin stalking the group.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Grant eventually escapes the island with Billy and the Kirbys.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Paul Kirby is a small-time businessman who is the owner of the hardware store Kirby Paint and Tile Plus.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] After his son Eric goes missing, Paul enlists the help of Grant under the disguise of being the wealthy owner of Kirby Enterprises and falsely promises to fund the latter's dig site in exchange for an aerial tour of Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] When the group is attacked by the *Spinosaurus* on a river, Paul uses himself as bait so the others can escape.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Director Joe Johnston enjoyed seeing unexpected actors in films: "You could think of a hundred actors who would be more apt to be stuck on an island, trying to survive among man-eating dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Bill Macy is not a name and a face that automatically springs to mind, but that's what makes it interesting".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Macy had been working with Laura Dern on the 2001 film *Focus*, and she convinced him to accept the role in *Jurassic Park III*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Macy originally turned it down due to scheduling conflicts.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Amanda Kirby is Paul's former wife who accompanies the search party to Site B to look for Eric and her boyfriend Ben.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] She frequently ignores Grant's warning to stay quiet and avoid attracting animals.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Ben's body is eventually found and she later reconciles with Paul.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The group is subsequently cornered by the raptor pack.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Amanda, the lone female among the humans, is confronted by a raptor mother and returns the stolen eggs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Leoni accepted the role after being contacted by Spielberg.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Her daughter had recently been ill, although she withheld her emotions to get through the event.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] After reading the film's script, Leoni felt that she could relate to Amanda Kirby, commenting that the story was about "a woman who had lost her child, albeit in a jungle with dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] She had not gotten into physical shape prior to the start of filming, which she described as "a really stupid move on my part. [...] I suffered for it.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Billy Brennan is a young and enthusiastic graduate student at Grant's dig site.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He later accompanies Grant to Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Grant is angry when he learns that Billy has taken raptor eggs, putting the humans at risk.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Later, Billy saves Eric from *Pteranodons*, but becomes separated from the others and is presumed dead.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He is rescued by the military, and reunited with Grant on a helicopter.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Nivola believes that the *Pteranodon* attack was initially meant to be Billy's last appearance in the film, resulting in his character's death.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He speculated that his character was brought back at the end of the film because of younger audiences' potential reactions.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Nivola criticized the film in 2002: "It was like the only part I've ever done that just had nothing for me to latch on to, character-wise. [...] It was kind of maddening".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Eric Kirby is the 12-year-old son of Paul and Amanda who is stranded for nearly eight weeks on Site B, and must fend for himself.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He later rescues Grant from velociraptors, and the two bond while on the island.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Spielberg had seen Morgan in *The Patriot* (2000), and Morgan also knew *Jurassic Park III* producer Kathleen Kennedy, after working with her on *The Sixth Sense* (1999).
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] A series of books written by Scott Ciencin follow Eric's time on Isla Sorna (as well as other related stories) before Grant and the others arrive.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] These books are *Jurassic Park Adventures: Survivor*, *Jurassic Park Adventures: Prey*, and *Jurassic Park Adventures: Flyers*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Udesky is part of the mercenary team hired by the Kirbys.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He describes himself as a booking agent, taking the place of another man who became ill.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The Kirbys took Udesky's advice to consult someone who had been on Isla Sorna before, but they realize later that Grant had only been to Isla Nublar.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] While on the island, Udesky gets separated from the others.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] A *Velociraptor* stabs Udesky's back with its toe claw, immobilizing him in an attempt to lure the other humans out to help him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] When this does not work, a raptor kills Udesky by snapping his neck.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Cooper is one of the mercenaries hired by the Kirbys.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] When Grant opposes landing on Isla Sorna, he is knocked unconscious by Cooper.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Shortly after landing, the mercenaries encounter the *Spinosaurus* and flee back to the plane.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Cooper is abandoned by his team and snatched up by the dinosaur.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He, along with Paul's satellite phone, is consumed by the *Spinosaurus* shortly after crashing on Site B.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Later, when the others hear the phone ringing from within the dinosaur's abdomen, they know the *Spinosaurus* is nearby.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The phone is eventually recovered from a pile of *Spinosaurus* feces.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Mark is Ellie's husband who works as a lawyer for the U.S.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] State Department, and specializes in international relations and treaty law.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] They have two young children, including Charlie.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] An early idea was for Nichols to shoot additional footage for the film's ending, although this was removed as the script went through revisions.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] In *Jurassic World Dominion*, set approximately 20 years after *Jurassic Park III*, Mark and Ellie are revealed to have divorced.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Ben Hildebrand is Amanda's boyfriend who takes Eric parasailing near Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] When the boat crew is killed, Ben saves Eric and himself by disconnecting the parasail from the vessel and gliding onto the island.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Although his cause of death is left unexplained, his decomposing corpse is found tangled in his parachute.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Enrique Cardoso is the operator of the illegal parasailing service called "Dino-Soar" which brings visitors to sight-see along the coast of Isla Sorna.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He is hired to take Ben and Eric to the island; however, Enrique and his boat driver are killed offscreen when they enter a fog bank, causing the vessel to crash and the tourists to become stranded on Site B.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] His cause of death is not explained in the film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Charlie is the three-year-old son of Ellie and Mark, and he has a younger sibling.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Grant contacts Ellie while being attacked by the *Spinosaurus*, but it is Charlie who answers the phone.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He is briefly distracted by an episode of *Barney & Friends*, before taking the phone to Ellie just in time for Grant to get his distress message through.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] In *Jurassic World Dominion*, it is mentioned that Ellie and Mark's children are in college.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] These characters are introduced in the fourth film, *Jurassic World* (2015).
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] In the film, a dinosaur theme park called Jurassic World has operated on Isla Nublar for years.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] It descends into chaos when a genetically modified hybrid dinosaur, the *Indominus rex*, escapes its enclosure.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Park manager Claire Dearing attempts to stop it with help from Owen Grady, a Navy veteran who is researching *Velociraptor* intelligence on the island.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The two also locate Claire's nephews, Zach and Gray, after they got lost while visiting the island.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Jurassic World owner Simon Masrani pilots an armed helicopter and tracks the *Indominus*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The dinosaur breaks into an aviary, releasing pterosaurs which cause havoc at the park.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Masrani is killed when his helicopter collides with the pterosaurs and crashes.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Hoskins, the head of security, uses Owen's raptors in a failed mission to take down the *Indominus*, which is later killed during a battle with several dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Owen, Claire, her nephews, and other survivors are evacuated, and the island is abandoned.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Owen Grady is one of the main protagonists of the *Jurassic World* trilogy.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] In the first film, he works as an animal behaviorist at Jurassic World, along with his friend Barry Sembène.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] They have been training four *Velociraptors* and researching their intelligence for InGen Security, led by Vic Hoskins.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Owen opposes Hoskins's long-term goal to use the raptors as military weapons.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Owen was once romantically attracted to Claire Dearing, though their conflicting personalities ended a potential relationship after one date.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] They rekindle their relationship by the end of the first film, but break up by the time that *Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom* takes place.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] In the latter film, three years have passed and Claire joins a rescue mission to save the Isla Nublar dinosaurs from an impending volcanic eruption.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The operation is organized by Sir Benjamin Lockwood, a former partner of John Hammond.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Owen has a close connection with Blue, the sole surviving raptor that he raised at Jurassic World, and he reluctantly joins the rescue mission in order to save Blue from the island.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Benjamin Lockwood is later killed, and Owen and Claire become adoptive parents to his granddaughter Maisie Lockwood, who is revealed to actually be a clone of his deceased daughter Charlotte.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] In *Jurassic World Dominion*, four years have passed since the events of the previous film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Owen and Claire live in the Sierra Nevada with Maisie, who is kidnapped by Biosyn for research purposes, along with Blue's asexually reproduced baby Beta.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Owen and Claire embark on a rescue mission to save them.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Claire Dearing is one of the main protagonists of the *Jurassic World* trilogy, alongside her romantic partner Owen.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] She is initially the park operations manager at the dinosaur theme park Jurassic World, and becomes a dinosaur rights activist in the later films, as well as adoptive mother to Maisie Lockwood.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] In *Jurassic World*, Claire is initially dismissive of Owen's warnings regarding the *Indominus*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Later, as Owen comforts a dying *Apatosaurus* that had been attacked by the *Indominus*, Claire emotionally bonds with it, altering her view of the park's dinosaurs as "assets".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Claire later lures the park's *Tyrannosaurus* into a battle with the *Indominus*, the latter of whom is killed in battle.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] In *Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom*, Claire is leading the Dinosaur Protection Group (DPG), an organization dedicated to saving the Isla Nublar dinosaurs from a volcanic eruption.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] She and Owen also become adoptive parents to Maisie, a clone of Benjamin Lockwood's deceased daughter.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] In *Jurassic World Dominion*, the couple set out to rescue Maisie after she is kidnapped by Biosyn for research purposes.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Some critics opined that the first film's depiction of Claire was sexist, including her use of high heels.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Zach Mitchell is Claire's 16-year-old nephew.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He is annoyed and embarrassed by Gray's enthusiasm for the dinosaur exhibits, and mostly ignores him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] When Gray becomes upset over their parents' impending divorce, Zach remains unsympathetic, ordering his little brother to grow up.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Although Zach has a girlfriend, he frequently stares at other girls around the park, to the annoyance of Gray.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Zach gradually becomes interested in the park as the two boys explore it.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] They later come upon the decaying remains of the original Jurassic Park Visitor Center, before making their way back to Jurassic World.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Their mother is frustrated by Zach's occasional meanness toward Gray, although the brothers eventually restore their bond during their vacation.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Gray Mitchell is Claire's 11-year-old nephew.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He is enthusiastic about dinosaurs and the theme park, to the annoyance of older brother Zach.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He is also upset by his parents' impending divorce.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] When Gray and Zach encounter the *Indominus*, they escape by jumping off a waterfall.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] They subsequently find the decaying remains of the original Jurassic Park Visitor Center, before returning to Jurassic World.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] During a final confrontation between Owen's raptors and the *Indominus*, Gray convinces Claire to lure the *Tyrannosaurus* into battle by claiming that they need "more teeth" to defeat the *Indominus*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Gray initially was written as a child with autism, but this trait was removed from the final script.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Simpkins performed all of his own stunts with the exception of the waterfall jump.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Simon Masrani is the CEO of Masrani Global Corporation and the owner of Jurassic World.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] In the film, it is stated that Masrani is the eighth richest man in the world, and that John Hammond entrusted Masrani with his dying wish to open the theme park.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] In 2014, a viral marketing website for the fictional Masrani Global Corporation was launched to promote *Jurassic World*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] According to the website, Masrani's father, Sanjay Masrani, started the company as a telecommunications business before eventually passing leadership to his son.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The business then expanded into the oil industry and bought InGen after the death of Hammond in 1997.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The website further states that in 2002, Masrani set out to construct Jurassic World, opening it three years later.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Masrani is joyful and makes his belief clear to park manager Claire that happiness is important for both the dinosaurs and park guests.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] When the *Indominus rex* escapes, he orders it captured alive since he has $26 million invested in it.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] When most of the ACU (short for Asset Containment Unit) team is wiped out, Masrani confronts the hybrid's creator Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Henry Wu who claims that he engineered it under Masrani's orders for "cooler" animals.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Though still in the process of earning his helicopter license, Masrani pilots a helicopter to track the *Indominus*, taking two ACU soldiers with him to kill the animal.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Fleeing from helicopter gunfire, the *Indominus* breaks into the park's aviary, letting loose *Pteranodons* and *Dimorphodons*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The pterosaurs collide with the helicopter which then plummets into the aviary, killing Masrani and several of the animals in the resulting explosion.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Khan described Masrani as "a very flamboyant person", and said that "he's trying to entertain the world with good intentions, but sometimes being flamboyant doesn't mean having much wisdom".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The Masrani website states that the company experienced its worst financial crisis following the events of *Jurassic World*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] In *Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom*, it is revealed that the Masrani Corporation paid more than 800 million in unspecified currency to settle class action lawsuits filed by the survivors of the Jurassic World disaster.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Another in-universe website was launched to promote *Fallen Kingdom* and it states that an investigation was initiated after the Jurassic World incident.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] It found that Masrani Global had bribed members of the US House Committee of Science to revise a law in 2003, thereby allowing the company to start cloning dinosaurs for the upcoming Jurassic World.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The investigation also found that Masrani Global had illegally cloned several dinosaur species prior to the 2003 revision.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] According to the website, it was unknown whether Simon Masrani had any knowledge of the illegal cloning.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Vic Hoskins is the head of InGen Security.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He is the secondary antagonist of *Jurassic World*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] According to the website, Hoskins attained the head position at InGen Security after overseeing the elimination of *Pteranodons* that escaped to Canada following the events of *Jurassic Park III*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Over time, he redeveloped and improved InGen Security.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Prior to events in *Jurassic World*, Hoskins had been involved in a two-year research program at the theme park meant to test the *Velociraptors*' intelligence.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] After observing the raptors obey Owen's commands, Hoskins desires to test them out as weaponized animals.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Hoskins is also shown to have a secret alliance with Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Henry Wu, creator of the *Indominus rex*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Following Masrani's death, Hoskins takes command and puts his raptor plan into effect to kill the *Indominus*, with Owen reluctantly taking part.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] When it fails, Hoskins and the InGen team prioritize the evacuation of the lab, saving dinosaur embryos and transporting them, along with Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Before Hoskins can leave, a raptor corners him in the lab and kills him.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Prior to his death, Hoskins had revealed to Owen and Claire that he intended to create miniature versions of the *Indominus rex* as weapons to keep InGen Security viable.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The *Indoraptor*, a smaller genetically engineered version of the *Indominus*, is later created by Dr.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Wu as a weaponized animal in *Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Lowery is the park's tech-savvy operations overseer and serves as the film's comic relief.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He is a fan of the first theme park and wears a vintage Jurassic Park T-shirt.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] This causes Claire to scold him, considering it to be in bad taste due to the events that took place there.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Lowery opposes the idea of genetically modified dinosaurs, believing it goes too far and that regular dinosaurs are superior.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He keeps a collection of toy dinosaurs on his desk, which Owen knocks off after becoming frustrated by the operations team, much to Lowery's dismay.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] After Hoskins assumes command, Lowery remains on duty in the control room and warns Claire about his plan to use the raptors to hunt the *Indominus*, an idea that Lowery considers insane.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] When the plan fails and an evacuation is called, Lowery opts to stay behind.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He tries to kiss Vivian - his close friend and coworker, who he has a crush on - before she leaves, but she deflects him, saying that she has a boyfriend.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Instead, he awkwardly shares a hug with her.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Claire later orders Lowery to release the *Tyrannosaurus* from her paddock to attack the *Indominus*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] After the *Indominus* is killed, Lowery shuts down the control room and leaves with a toy sauropod.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Johnson previously had a role in Trevorrow's 2012 film *Safety Not Guaranteed*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] For *Jurassic World*, he worked with Trevorrow and co-writer Derek Connolly to make a backstory for the character, creating details that went unmentioned in the film.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Johnson said, "We view Lowery as the kind of guy who would be obsessed with the original Jurassic Park.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Not the movie, but the actual park, but was too young to have gone.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] We see him as a guy that, after college and Jurassic World came about, felt like he couldn't pass up the opportunity to work there.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He's a guy who's working there in that control room in order to be close to the dinosaurs everyday".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Johnson viewed Lowery as a voice for the audience in his critique of hybrid dinosaurs: "My character is basically saying a lot of times, well, why are they doing that?" After the film's release, Lowery quickly became a fan-favorite character.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Trevorrow considered bringing Lowery back for *Jurassic World: Fallen Kingdom* but eventually created an equivalent character named Franklin Webb because he considered Lowery too cynical to take part in the sequel's plot.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Before being written out, Johnson had discussed his potential role with Connolly, later saying that Lowery "is a different guy because of what he went through in the first movie.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] The trauma of seeing a dinosaur attack really messed him up.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Johnson was initially set to reprise the role in *Jurassic World Dominion*, but scheduling conflicts caused by the COVID-19 pandemic resulted in the character being written out.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] However, Lowery briefly appears in a picture on Franklin Webb's tablet, revealing that he now works for the CIA's Dangerous Species Division along with Vivian.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Barry Sembène is Owen Grady's assistant and friend who helps cares for the four *Velociraptors* at Jurassic World.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Like Owen, Barry argues with Hoskins that *Velociraptors* cannot be used as military animals, though he reluctantly participates with Owen in leading the raptor hunt for the *Indominus*.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He is later pursued by the raptor Blue and takes cover inside a hollow log.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] She attempts to break it open, causing him to draw his pistol in defense.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Unable to bring himself to shoot Blue, he instead calls out her name, which briefly halts the attack.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Owen is able to distract Blue, allowing Barry to escape.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He later evacuates the island with other survivors.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Trevorrow had admired Sy's acting and wrote the character of Barry with him in mind for the role.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Trevorrow wrote a friendship between Owen and Barry that "could be memorable and potentially carry on to future films".
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Sy reprises the role in *Jurassic World Dominion*, reuniting with Pratt.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Barry now works as an agent for French intelligence, helping to protect escaped dinosaurs.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He helps Owen and Claire take down a dinosaur black market in search of their missing adopted daughter Maisie Lockwood.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] He later arrests Soyona Santos, a high-ranking member of the black market operation.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Barry reappears in season 3 of *Jurassic World: Chaos Theory* where he encounters the Nublar Six in their mutual pursuit of Santos.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] After being captured by Barry in *Dominion*, Santos escapes by setting off a bomb, trapping Barry in debris.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Barry is rescued by Ben Pincus and Davi who lead him to where Santos is preparing to make her escape.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Barry finally arrests Santos and allows Darius, Brooklynn, Ben and Yasmine to take Santos' escape helicopter to Biosyn.
[src:jurassic-park-novel/alexis-lex-murphy-p04] Karen and Scott Mitchell are Claire Dearing's sister and brother-in-law, respectively.
